<p class="s13">“TO BE” IN PRESENT SIMPLE. SUBJECT PRONOUNS</p><p><span><IMG width="118" height="87" src="https://app.oxbridge.es/app/movil/FT/Manual S1/Image_009.png"/></span></p><p class="s14">Students<span class="p">: Use this structure when you want to introduce yourself and/or others. Here are some examples:</span></p><p>1. “Hello, <b>I am </b>Adriana Garcia.”<br/><span><IMG width="125" height="176" src="https://app.oxbridge.es/app/movil/FT/Manual S1/Image_010.jpg"/></span><br/>2. “<b>You are </b>an English student.”</p><p class="s16">I love toys!</p><p class="s16">English is easy!</p><p><span><IMG width="274" height="204" src="https://app.oxbridge.es/app/movil/FT/Manual S1/Image_011.png"/></span><br/><span><IMG width="178" height="178" src="https://app.oxbridge.es/app/movil/FT/Manual S1/Image_012.png"/></span><br/><span><IMG width="118" height="83" src="https://app.oxbridge.es/app/movil/FT/Manual S1/Image_013.png"/></span><br/>3. “<b>She is </b>from Columbia.” “He is from Mexico”.</p><p class="s16">I am from</p><p class="s16">Columbia</p><p class="s16">.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p class="s13">“TO BE” IN PRESENT SIMPLE. SUBJECT PRONOUNS</p><p><span><IMG width="421" height="202" src="https://app.oxbridge.es/app/movil/FT/Manual S1/Image_015.png"/></span><br/>4. “<b>We are </b>Spanish.”</p><p class="s16">We are the Tuna!</p><p><span><IMG width="281" height="237" src="https://app.oxbridge.es/app/movil/FT/Manual S1/Image_016.png"/></span></p><p class="s14">Students<span class="p">: Remember that with this structure you can also talk about yourself and other people using the negative format.</span></p><p>1. “<b>I am not </b>Brad Pitt”</p><p class="s16">Are you</p><p class="s16">Brad Pitt?</p><p>2. “<b>You are not </b>a doctor.”<br/>
  <br/><span><IMG width="353" height="170" src="https://app.oxbridge.es/app/movil/FT/Manual S1/Image_018.png"/></span></p><p class="s13">“TO BE” IN PRESENT SIMPLE. SUBJECT PRONOUNS</p><p class="s16">I am Dr. Clooney!</p><p><span><IMG width="271" height="210" src="https://app.oxbridge.es/app/movil/FT/Manual S1/Image_019.png"/></span><br/>. “<b>He is not </b>from Korea.”</p><p class="s16">I am from</p><p class="s16">China!</p><p><span><IMG width="225" height="226" src="https://app.oxbridge.es/app/movil/FT/Manual S1/Image_020.png"/></span><br/><span><IMG width="177" height="106" src="https://app.oxbridge.es/app/movil/FT/Manual S1/Image_021.png"/></span><br/>4. “<b>They are not </b>American.”</p><p class="s16">We are Oreja de Van Gogh from Spain.</p><p><span><IMG width="130" height="140" src="https://app.oxbridge.es/app/movil/FT/Manual S1/Image_022.png"/></span></p><p class="s14">Students<span class="p">: You can also use this structure to ask questions about other people. Here are some examples:</span></p><p class="s16">Are you</p><p class="s16">rich and famous?</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p class="s13">“TO BE” IN PRESENT SIMPLE. SUBJECT PRONOUNS</p><p><span><IMG width="296" height="223" src="https://app.oxbridge.es/app/movil/FT/Manual S1/Image_024.jpg"/></span><br/>1. “<b>Are you </b>rich and famous?”<br/>2. “<b>Is he </b>happy?”</p><p class="s16">I hate this woman!</p><p><span><IMG width="304" height="234" src="https://app.oxbridge.es/app/movil/FT/Manual S1/Image_025.png"/></span><br/><span><IMG width="341" height="270" src="https://app.oxbridge.es/app/movil/FT/Manual S1/Image_026.png"/></span><br/>3. “<b>Are we not </b>going to Hawaii?”</p><p class="s16">We are arriving to Barcelona in</p><p class="s16">5 minutes.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p class="s13">“TO BE” IN PRESENT SIMPLE. SUBJECT PRONOUNS</p><p><span><IMG width="401" height="213" src="https://app.oxbridge.es/app/movil/FT/Manual S1/Image_028.png"/></span><br/>4. “<b>Is it not </b>your new dog?”</p><p class="s16">My name is</p><p class="s16">Tequila ☺</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p class="s13">“TO BE” IN PRESENT SIMPLE. QUESTIONS, SHORT ANSWERS AND NEGATIVE FORMS</p><p class="s15">Students: <span class="p">You want to use this structure, ‘to be’, when you want to express a characteristic. Here you will find how to use it in questions, short answers and in the negative form.</span></p><p>Formula:<br/>Affirmative: we use the basic forms of “to be”.<br/>E.g.    <b>I am </b>a panda bear. <b>We are </b>students.<br/>Negative: we add NOT after “to be”.<br/>E.g.    <b>I am not </b>a panda bear. <b>I’m not </b>a panda bear.</p><p class="s15">We are not <span class="p">students. </span>We aren’t <span class="p">students.</span></p><p>Questions: we invert the order of the verb “to be”.<br/>E.g.    <b>Am I </b>a panda bear?</p><p class="s15">Are we <span class="p">students?</span></p><p>Short answers: we use YES or NO, and the verb “to be”.<br/>E.g.    Yes, <b>I am</b>. // No, <b>I am not</b>.<br/>Yes, <b>we are</b>. // No, <b>we are not</b>. No, <b>we aren’t.</b><br/>Here are some examples: (a) <u>Affirmative:</u><br/>I am a panda bear! (I’m a panda bear!)<br/><span><IMG width="162" height="151" src="https://app.oxbridge.es/app/movil/FT/Manual S1/Image_030.jpg"/></span><br/>We are wild animals. (We’re wild animals)<br/>
  </p><p class="s13">“TO BE” IN PRESENT SIMPLE. QUESTIONS, SHORT ANSWERS AND NEGATIVE FORMS</p><p><span><IMG width="234" height="199" src="https://app.oxbridge.es/app/movil/FT/Manual S1/Image_032.gif"/></span><br/>She is a happy horse. (She’s a happy horse)<br/><span><IMG width="158" height="210" src="https://app.oxbridge.es/app/movil/FT/Manual S1/Image_033.jpg"/></span><br/>(b) <u>Negative</u>:<br/>I am not a panda bear! (I’m not a panda bear!)<br/><span><IMG width="158" height="208" src="https://app.oxbridge.es/app/movil/FT/Manual S1/Image_034.jpg"/></span><br/>We are not wild animals. (We’re not wild animals. // We aren’t wild animals.)<br/>
  </p><p class="s13">“TO BE” IN PRESENT SIMPLE. QUESTIONS, SHORT ANSWERS AND NEGATIVE FORMS</p><p><span><IMG width="328" height="216" src="https://app.oxbridge.es/app/movil/FT/Manual S1/Image_036.jpg"/></span><br/>He is not a happy animal. (He’s not a happy animal. // He isn’t a happy animal.)<br/><span><IMG width="188" height="241" src="https://app.oxbridge.es/app/movil/FT/Manual S1/Image_037.jpg"/></span><br/>(c) <u>Question</u>:</p><p class="s16">-    <span class="p">Am I panda bear?!?!</span></p><p class="s16">-    <span class="p">No, I’m not! (Yes, I am.)</span></p><p class="s13">“TO BE” IN PRESENT SIMPLE. QUESTIONS, SHORT ANSWERS AND NEGATIVE FORMS</p><p><span><IMG width="229" height="160" src="https://app.oxbridge.es/app/movil/FT/Manual S1/Image_039.jpg"/></span></p><p class="s16">-    <span class="p">Are we wild animals?!?!</span></p><p class="s16">-    <span class="p">No, we are not. (No, we aren’t). // Yes, we are.</span></p><p><span><IMG width="238" height="177" src="https://app.oxbridge.es/app/movil/FT/Manual S1/Image_040.gif"/></span></p><p class="s16">-    <span class="p">Are they wild animals?</span></p><p class="s16">-    <span class="p">Yes, they are. // No, they are not. (No, they’re not. No, they aren’t,)</span></p><p><span><IMG width="204" height="211" src="https://app.oxbridge.es/app/movil/FT/Manual S1/Image_041.jpg"/></span><br/>
  </p><p class="s13">BASIC QUESTIONS WITH “TO BE” AND “WHAT, WHERE, WHO”</p><p><u><b>Students</b></u>: Please learn this structure because it is very important. With this English Structure you will learn how to make simple questions about places (locations), things (objects), and people. If you want to know something use “<b>what</b>”, but if you want to know a place use “<b>where</b>”, and if you want to know a person use “<b>who</b>”.<br/>Here are some examples:</p><p class="s15">(a) “What” Question:</p><p>You want to use this type of question when you want to ask a question about something. The format of this question is:</p><p class="s15">What + “to be” + subject? (What is it?)</p><p>There is no verb change in the question, but there is a verb change in the answer if it includes an action. For example: What is your favorite sport? My favorite sport is jogging. In a normal answer, the format is:</p><p class="s15">Subject + “to be” + “thing” (It is a car.)</p><p class="s15">(example subjects: I, you, s/he, it, we, you, they)</p><p>Here are some examples:<br/>-    What is your favorite food?<br/>My favorite food is cannelloni.<br/><span><IMG width="353" height="209" src="https://app.oxbridge.es/app/movil/FT/Manual S1/Image_043.jpg"/></span><br/>
  </p><p class="s13">BASIC QUESTIONS WITH “TO BE” AND “WHAT, WHERE, WHO”</p><p>-    What is their favorite film?<br/>Their favorite film is “Sixteen Candles”.<br/><span><IMG width="171" height="244" src="https://app.oxbridge.es/app/movil/FT/Manual S1/Image_045.jpg"/></span></p><p class="s15">(b) “Where” Question:</p><p>You want to use this type of question when you want to know the location         of a place, person or thing. Here is the format for these questions:</p><p class="s15">Where + “to be” + subject?</p><p class="s15">(example subjects: I, you, s/he, it, we, you, they)</p><p>Here are some examples:<br/>-    Where are you? I am in the USA.<br/>
  </p><p class="s13">BASIC QUESTIONS WITH “TO BE” AND “WHAT, WHERE, WHO”</p><p><span><IMG width="313" height="225" src="https://app.oxbridge.es/app/movil/FT/Manual S1/Image_047.gif"/></span><br/>-    Where is this island?<br/>This island is in the Pacific Ocean.<br/><span><IMG width="341" height="255" src="https://app.oxbridge.es/app/movil/FT/Manual S1/Image_048.jpg"/></span></p><p class="s15">(c) “Who” Question:</p><p>You want to use this type of question when you want to ask a question about a person. Here is the format of this type of question:</p><p class="s15">Who + “to be”+ subject? (Who is she?)</p><p class="s15">(example subjects: I, you, s/he, it, we, you, they)</p><p>Here is the format for the answers:</p><p class="s15">Subject + “to be” + person/people (She is my sister.)</p><p class="s13">BASIC QUESTIONS WITH “TO BE” AND “WHAT, WHERE, WHO”</p><p>Here are some examples:<br/>-    Who is that man? He is my brother.<br/><span><IMG width="175" height="176" src="https://app.oxbridge.es/app/movil/FT/Manual S1/Image_050.jpg"/></span><br/><span><IMG width="173" height="210" src="https://app.oxbridge.es/app/movil/FT/Manual S1/Image_051.jpg"/></span><br/>-    Who is your best friend? Tobby is my best friend.<br/><b>**Note: </b>When you want to ask a question you can also use “Do/Does”. We can use <i>do </i>and <i>does </i>do make yes-no questions in the simple present tense. We can also use these auxiliaries to make the short answers to the same<br/>yes-no questions.<br/>Here is the question and answer format:</p><p class="s15">Do/Does + subject + infinitive? (QUESTIONS)</p><p>(Use “<b>do</b>” for: <b>I, you, we, they </b>AND use “<b>does</b>” for: <b>she, he, it</b>)<br/>
  </p><p class="s13">BASIC QUESTIONS WITH “TO BE” AND “WHAT, WHERE, WHO” <span class="s15">Yes/No + subject + do/does/don’t/doesn’t (ANSWERS +/-) </span><span class="p">Here are some examples:</span></p><p>(a) Do you like cheese?<br/>Yes, I do!<br/><span><IMG width="185" height="202" src="https://app.oxbridge.es/app/movil/FT/Manual S1/Image_053.jpg"/></span><br/>(b) Does s/he live in a big house?<br/>Yes, s/he does.<br/><span><IMG width="276" height="199" src="https://app.oxbridge.es/app/movil/FT/Manual S1/Image_054.jpg"/></span><br/>(c) Do I look beautiful?<br/>No, you don’t<br/>€ (d) Does his car run?<br/>No, it doesn’t.<br/>
  </p><p class="s13">BASIC QUESTIONS WITH “TO BE” AND “WHAT, WHERE, WHO”</p><p><span><IMG width="246" height="183" src="https://app.oxbridge.es/app/movil/FT/Manual S1/Image_056.jpg"/></span><br/>
  </p><p class="s13">THE USE OF “THERE IS/THERE ARE” IN AFFIRMATIVE, INTERROGATIVE AND NEGATIVE FORMS</p><p>Students: You want to use this structure when you want to talk about objects that are in your sight or surroundings and exist, but are not 100% visible. When you want talk about an object use “<b>there is</b>” (singular). If you want to do the same,<br/>but in plural you use “<b>there are</b>”.<br/>Here is the structures of this theory:<br/>Affirmative, 1 thing (singular)                “There is” + a/an/one + object<br/>Negative, 1 thing (singular)                   “There is” + no + object<br/>OR     “There is” + not + any + object<br/>Question, 1 thing (singular)                   “Is there” + any + object?<br/>Affirmative, many things                        “There are” + objects</p><table border="1" cellspacing="0" style="border-collapse:collapse"><tr><td><p class="s19">Negative, many things</p></td><td/><td><p class="s19">“There are” + no + objects</p></td></tr><tr><td/><td><p class="s19">OR</p></td><td><p class="s19">“There are” + not + any + objects</p></td></tr><tr><td><p class="s19">Question, many things</p></td><td/><td><p class="s19">“Are there” + any + objects?</p></td></tr></table><p class="s15">Answers<span class="p">: They are quite simple:</span></p><p>Yes, there is (are).                      OR                No, there is not. (No, there isn’t).<br/>aren’t).</p><p class="s20">Contractions<span class="s21">:</span></p><p>No, there are not.  (No, there</p><p class="s15">There is = there’s                                            There is not = There isn’t</p><p class="s15">BUT: There are =/= there’re (wrong!) There are not = There aren’t</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p class="s13">THE USE OF “THERE IS/THERE ARE” IN AFFIRMATIVE, INTERROGATIVE AND NEGATIVE FORMS</p><p>Here are some examples:</p><p class="s15">(a) Affirmative Form:</p><p><span><IMG width="374" height="242" src="https://app.oxbridge.es/app/movil/FT/Manual S1/Image_059.png"/></span><br/>-    There is one cat in my house. (There’s a cat in my house).</p><p class="s16">Hi, I’m</p><p class="s16">Taketas!</p><p><span><IMG width="459" height="284" src="https://app.oxbridge.es/app/movil/FT/Manual S1/Image_060.png"/></span><br/>-    There are many children in the house.</p><p class="s16">We are trouble! ☺</p><p class="s13">THE USE OF “THERE IS/THERE ARE” IN AFFIRMATIVE, INTERROGATIVE AND NEGATIVE FORMS</p><p><span><IMG width="418" height="391" src="https://app.oxbridge.es/app/movil/FT/Manual S1/Image_062.png"/></span></p><p class="s15">(b) Negative Form:</p><p>-    There is no food in the fridge.</p><p class="s16">HELP!</p><p><span><IMG width="453" height="276" src="https://app.oxbridge.es/app/movil/FT/Manual S1/Image_063.png"/></span><br/>-    There are no monkeys in the zoo.</p><p class="s16">I am too intelligent to be in a zoo!</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p class="s13">THE USE OF “THERE IS/THERE ARE” IN AFFIRMATIVE, INTERROGATIVE AND NEGATIVE FORMS</p><p class="s15">(c) Question Form:</p><p><span><IMG width="400" height="384" src="https://app.oxbridge.es/app/movil/FT/Manual S1/Image_065.png"/></span><br/>-    Is there any money in the piggy bank?</p><p class="s22">I have lots of money!</p><p><span><IMG width="226" height="232" src="https://app.oxbridge.es/app/movil/FT/Manual S1/Image_066.jpg"/></span><br/><span><IMG width="149" height="107" src="https://app.oxbridge.es/app/movil/FT/Manual S1/Image_067.png"/></span><br/>-    Are there any students in the class?</p><p class="s16">Yes, there are 4 students.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p class="s13">“THIS IS / THESE ARE”. THE USE OF “IT” AND “THERE”</p><p class="s15">Students: <span class="p">This structure is very useful when you want to talk about the objects/people that are very near to you. &quot;</span>This<span class="p">&quot; is used when you want to talk about a singular object. It is used when talking about an object or person near the speaker. &quot;</span>These<span class="p">&quot; is the plural form of &quot;</span>this<span class="p">&quot;.  It is used in the same format, but with many things or people.</span></p><p class="s17">1 object<span class="p">                                                                </span>2 or more objects.</p><p><span><IMG width="524" height="212" src="https://app.oxbridge.es/app/movil/FT/Manual S1/Image_069.png"/></span></p><p class="s15">This <span class="p">– for 1 object near you.                               </span>These <span class="p">– for 2 or more object near you.</span></p><p>This is my computer!<br/>These are my friends!<br/><span><IMG width="433" height="179" src="https://app.oxbridge.es/app/movil/FT/Manual S1/Image_070.png"/></span><br/><span><IMG width="94" height="83" src="https://app.oxbridge.es/app/movil/FT/Manual S1/Image_071.png"/></span></p><p class="s15">That <span class="p">– for 1 object far from you.                         </span>Those <span class="p">– for 2 or more object far from you.</span></p><p><span><IMG width="107" height="167" src="https://app.oxbridge.es/app/movil/FT/Manual S1/Image_072.jpg"/></span><br/>That’s my village!<br/>“<b>This” </b>and “<b>That” </b>can be substituted by <b>“it” </b>in a beginning of a sentence when you want to identify an object (singular).<br/>For example: &lt;<b>This is </b>my dog. <b>It </b>is black.<br/>&lt; Is <b>that </b>your dog? Yes, <b>it </b>is./Yes, it’s my dog.&gt;<br/>And “<b>they</b>” is the plural form of “<b>it</b>”: “Are <b>these </b>your clothes? Yes, <b>they are.”</b><br/>Those dogs are mine!<br/>
  </p><p class="s13">“THIS IS / THESE ARE”. THE USE OF “IT” AND “THERE”</p><p>Here is the format of these structures:<br/>1.  QUESTIONS:<br/>“<b>Is this/that</b>” + a/an + object? (SINGULAR) “<b>Are these/those</b>” + objects (PLURAL)<br/>2.  AFFIRMATIVE SENTENCE:<br/>“<b>This/that is</b>” + a/an + object (SINGULAR) “<b>These/those are</b>” + objects (PLURAL)<br/>3.  NEGATIVE ANSWER:<br/>“<b>This/that is</b>” + not + a/an + object (SINGULAR) “<b>These/those are</b>” + not + objects (PLURAL)<br/>4.  “IT IS ” AFFIRMATIVE and NAGATIVE SENTENCE: “<b>It is</b>” + a/an + object<br/>“<b>It is</b>” + not + a/an + object<br/>5.  “THEY ARE” AFFIRMATIVE and NAGATIVE SENTENCE: “<b>They are</b>” + objects<br/>“<b>They are</b>” + not + objects<br/>Here are some examples of this structure in use:<br/>1.  QUESTIONS:<br/>(a) <b>Is this </b>your dog?<br/>Yes, <b>it is</b>. / Yes, <b>it is </b>my dog.<br/>No, <b>it is not</b>. / No, <b>it is not </b>my dog.<br/><span><IMG width="184" height="139" src="https://app.oxbridge.es/app/movil/FT/Manual S1/Image_074.jpg"/></span><br/>
  </p><p class="s13">“THIS IS / THESE ARE”. THE USE OF “IT” AND “THERE”</p><p>(b) <b>Are these </b>her sisters?<br/>Yes, <b>they are</b>. / Yes, <b>they are </b>her sisters.<br/>No, <b>they are not</b>. / No, <b>they are not </b>her sisters.<br/><span><IMG width="150" height="232" src="https://app.oxbridge.es/app/movil/FT/Manual S1/Image_076.jpg"/></span><br/>2.  AFFIRMATIVE SENTENCE: (a) <b>This is </b>his brother.<br/><span><IMG width="236" height="164" src="https://app.oxbridge.es/app/movil/FT/Manual S1/Image_077.png"/></span><br/>(b) <b>These are </b>our cars.<br/><span><IMG width="251" height="182" src="https://app.oxbridge.es/app/movil/FT/Manual S1/Image_078.jpg"/></span><br/>
  </p><p class="s13">“THIS IS / THESE ARE”. THE USE OF “IT” AND “THERE”</p><p>3.  NEGATIVE ANSWER: (a) <b>This is not </b>my bike.<br/><span><IMG width="211" height="314" src="https://app.oxbridge.es/app/movil/FT/Manual S1/Image_080.png"/></span><br/>(b) <b>These are not </b>her bags.<br/><span><IMG width="440" height="254" src="https://app.oxbridge.es/app/movil/FT/Manual S1/Image_081.jpg"/></span><br/>
  </p><p class="s13">THE ARTICLES: DEFINITE, INDEFINITE, ZERO</p><p>STUDENTS: Please be aware that this is a very important structure. It is<br/>important because many non-native English speakers have a lot of problems with this structure because they confuse one article for another or use or don’t use an article when necessary or not necessary. Here are the basic rules for the articles “A, An or The”:</p><p class="s15">A <span class="p">= indefinite article (not a specific object, one of a number of the same objects) with consonants</span></p><p class="s18">Homer eats <b>a </b>doughnut.</p><p><span><IMG width="129" height="159" src="https://app.oxbridge.es/app/movil/FT/Manual S1/Image_083.gif"/></span></p><p class="s15">An <span class="p">= indefinite article (not a specific object, one of a number of the same objects) with vowels (a, e, i, o, u)</span></p><p class="s18">Can I have <b>an </b>apple?</p><p><span><IMG width="108" height="155" src="https://app.oxbridge.es/app/movil/FT/Manual S1/Image_084.jpg"/></span></p><p class="s15">The <span class="p">= definite article (a specific object that both the person speaking and the listener know)</span></p><p class="s21">The <span class="s18">car is fast.</span></p><p><span><IMG width="191" height="134" src="https://app.oxbridge.es/app/movil/FT/Manual S1/Image_085.jpg"/></span><br/>
  </p><p class="s13">THE ARTICLES: DEFINITE, INDEFINITE, ZERO</p><p>The first time you speak of something use &quot;<b>a </b>or <b>an</b>&quot;, the next time you repeat that object use &quot;<b>the</b>&quot;.</p><p class="s18">I live in <b>a </b>house. <b>The </b>house is quite old and has two</p><p class="s18">bedrooms.</p><p><span><IMG width="338" height="273" src="https://app.oxbridge.es/app/movil/FT/Manual S1/Image_087.png"/></span></p><p class="s17">DO NOT<span class="p"> use an article with countries, states, counties or provinces, lakes and mountains except when the country is a collection of states such as &quot;The United States&quot;.</span></p><p class="s18">They live in California.</p><p><span><IMG width="260" height="297" src="https://app.oxbridge.es/app/movil/FT/Manual S1/Image_088.jpg"/></span><br/>
  </p><p class="s13">THE ARTICLES: DEFINITE, INDEFINITE, ZERO</p><p>Use an article with bodies of water, oceans and seas -</p><p class="s18">I live on a small island in <b>the </b>Baltic Sea.</p><p><span><IMG width="263" height="175" src="https://app.oxbridge.es/app/movil/FT/Manual S1/Image_090.jpg"/></span></p><p class="s17">DO NOT<span class="p"> use an article when you are speaking about things in general</span></p><p class="s18">I like Indian tea.</p><p><span><IMG width="272" height="214" src="https://app.oxbridge.es/app/movil/FT/Manual S1/Image_091.jpg"/></span></p><p class="s17">DO NOT<span class="p"> use an article when you are speaking about meals, places, and transport</span></p><p class="s18">She has breakfast at home.</p><p><span><IMG width="128" height="168" src="https://app.oxbridge.es/app/movil/FT/Manual S1/Image_092.jpg"/></span><br/>
  </p><p class="s13">THE ARTICLES: DEFINITE, INDEFINITE, ZERO</p><p>Yes, there are a lot of rules, but they are important and an easy way to remember when and when not to use articles.<br/>Here are some more examples in use:<br/>1.  The article “A”:</p><p class="s18">Eric has <b>a </b>dog.</p><p><span><IMG width="262" height="210" src="https://app.oxbridge.es/app/movil/FT/Manual S1/Image_094.jpg"/></span><br/>2.  The article “An”:</p><p class="s18">Adriana is <b>an </b>English teacher.</p><p class="s18">(Radmila (Ox Boss), Adriana, Jonatan (Ox Boss)</p><p><span><IMG width="410" height="308" src="https://app.oxbridge.es/app/movil/FT/Manual S1/Image_095.png"/></span><br/>
  </p><p class="s13">THE ARTICLES: DEFINITE, INDEFINITE, ZERO</p><p>3.  The article “The”:</p><p class="s21">The <span class="s18">science teacher is very good.</span></p><p><span><IMG width="184" height="245" src="https://app.oxbridge.es/app/movil/FT/Manual S1/Image_097.gif"/></span><br/>4.  1<span class="s23">st </span>encounter and reencounter:</p><p class="s18">I ate in <b>a </b>Japanese  restaurant. <b>The </b>restaurant was not very clean.</p><p><span><IMG width="396" height="297" src="https://app.oxbridge.es/app/movil/FT/Manual S1/Image_098.jpg"/></span><br/>
  </p><p class="s13">THE ARTICLES: DEFINITE, INDEFINITE, ZERO</p><p>5.  <b>NO </b>article with countries, states, counties or provinces, lakes and mountains (except the U.S., the Netherlands, etc.):</p><p class="s18">My uncle lives in Kenya.</p><p><span><IMG width="244" height="209" src="https://app.oxbridge.es/app/movil/FT/Manual S1/Image_100.jpg"/></span><br/>6.  Article for all bodies of water:</p><p class="s18">I like <b>the </b>Atlantic Ocean.</p><p><span><IMG width="280" height="210" src="https://app.oxbridge.es/app/movil/FT/Manual S1/Image_101.png"/></span><br/>7.  <u>NO</u> article when talking about general things:</p><p class="s18">Simon likes reading books.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p class="s13">THE ARTICLES: DEFINITE, INDEFINITE, ZERO</p><p><span><IMG width="175" height="163" src="https://app.oxbridge.es/app/movil/FT/Manual S1/Image_103.png"/></span><br/>8.  <u>NO</u> article when talking about meals, places, and transport:</p><p class="s18">I go to university.</p><p><span><IMG width="147" height="228" src="https://app.oxbridge.es/app/movil/FT/Manual S1/Image_104.jpg"/></span></p><p class="s18">Jane goes to work by taxi.</p><p><span><IMG width="239" height="223" src="https://app.oxbridge.es/app/movil/FT/Manual S1/Image_105.png"/></span><br/>
  </p><p class="s13">ANSKING AND SAYING THE AGE. THE NUMBERS. FRACTIONS AND DECIMALS</p><p class="s15">Numbers from 1 to 100. Practice the pronunciation with your teacher!</p><p>Attention to: 13 and 30, and 14 and 40, etc.</p><p class="s15">How to say your age.</p><p><span><IMG width="220" height="204" src="https://app.oxbridge.es/app/movil/FT/Manual S1/Image_107.png"/></span><br/><span><IMG width="118" height="87" src="https://app.oxbridge.es/app/movil/FT/Manual S1/Image_108.png"/></span><br/>In English we don’t use “have” like in Spanish/Catalan to know the age of a person, instead the answer is usually with the verb “TO BE” and the number. For example, <i>“How old are you? I am 24” and “how old is you sister? She is 17.”</i></p><table border="1" cellspacing="0" style="border-collapse:collapse"><tr><td><p class="s19">- How old are you?</p></td><td><p class="s19">- How old is she?</p></td><td><p class="s19">- How old are they?</p></td></tr><tr><td><p class="s19">- I’m eight! (8)</p></td><td><p class="s19">- She’s eighteen. (18)</p></td><td><p class="s19">- They are eighty.</p></td></tr><tr><td><p class="s19">(80)</p></td><td/><td/></tr></table><p>I’m 8!<br/>I can drive!<br/>We are happy!<br/><span><IMG width="221" height="401" src="https://app.oxbridge.es/app/movil/FT/Manual S1/Image_109.png"/></span><br/>Here is some more information on the use of cardinal and ordinal numbers:</p><p class="s15">CARDINAL NUMBERS</p><p>153= one hundred and fifty three<br/>3,034= three thousand and thirty-four<br/>3,550,000= three million, five hundred and fifty thousand<br/>7,000,000,000= seven billion<br/>
  </p><p class="s13">ANSKING AND SAYING THE AGE. THE NUMBERS. FRACTIONS AND DECIMALS</p><p>Note: There is no plural’s’ after hundred, thousand, million and billion when they form part of another number. On their own, they can be plural, e.g. Thousands of animals, millions of children.</p><p class="s15">ORDINAL NUMBERS AND THE DATES</p><p>Here you have some information on the use of dates:</p><p class="s15">19<i>97</i><span class="p">= nineteen ninety seven</span></p><p class="s15">19<i>05</i><span class="p">= nineteen oh five</span></p><p class="s15">FRACTIONS AND DECIMALS</p><p>1 1/4= one and a quarter<br/>1 1/2= one and a half<br/>1 3/4= one and three quarters<br/>1 1/3= one and a third<br/>1.25= one point two five<br/>1.5= one point five<br/>1.75= one point seven five<br/>1.63= one point six three</p><p class="s15">Students: <span class="p">here is the structure in use of cardinal and ordinal numbers:</span></p><p><span><IMG width="128" height="222" src="https://app.oxbridge.es/app/movil/FT/Manual S1/Image_111.jpg"/></span><br/>1.  What is your phone number? My number is 08015. (zero eight zero one five)<br/>
  </p><p class="s13">ANSKING AND SAYING THE AGE. THE NUMBERS. FRACTIONS AND DECIMALS</p><p><span><IMG width="438" height="316" src="https://app.oxbridge.es/app/movil/FT/Manual S1/Image_113.gif"/></span><br/>2.  When was Barcelona founded? Barcelona was founded in 1107. (eleven o seven)<br/>3.  When did Cervantes write “Don Quixote”? Cervantes wrote “Don Quixote”<br/><span><IMG width="179" height="244" src="https://app.oxbridge.es/app/movil/FT/Manual S1/Image_114.jpg"/></span><br/>in 1500. (fifteen hundred)<br/>4.  When was Pans and Company established? It was established in 1982. (nineteen eighty-two)<br/><span><IMG width="400" height="127" src="https://app.oxbridge.es/app/movil/FT/Manual S1/Image_115.png"/></span><br/>
  </p><p class="s13">ANSKING AND SAYING THE AGE. THE NUMBERS. FRACTIONS AND DECIMALS</p><p>5.  When did you visit 1<span class="s23">st </span>visit London? I 1<span class="s23">st </span>(first) visited London in 1993. (nineteen ninety-three)<br/><span><IMG width="413" height="268" src="https://app.oxbridge.es/app/movil/FT/Manual S1/Image_117.jpg"/></span><br/>6.  When did Bulgaria join the European Union? Bulgaria joined the EU in<br/>2007. (two-thousand seven)<br/><span><IMG width="242" height="221" src="https://app.oxbridge.es/app/movil/FT/Manual S1/Image_118.gif"/></span><br/><span><IMG width="165" height="213" src="https://app.oxbridge.es/app/movil/FT/Manual S1/Image_119.jpg"/></span><br/>7.  How much money do you have? I have 20.000 euros. (twenty-thousand)<br/><span><IMG width="170" height="178" src="https://app.oxbridge.es/app/movil/FT/Manual S1/Image_120.jpg"/></span><br/>
  </p><p class="s13">ANSKING AND SAYING THE AGE. THE NUMBERS. FRACTIONS AND DECIMALS</p><p>8.  How much pizza do you want? I want ¼. (one fourth)<br/><span><IMG width="208" height="208" src="https://app.oxbridge.es/app/movil/FT/Manual S1/Image_122.jpg"/></span><br/>9.  How fast did you run a kilometer? I finished in 3.4 minutes. (three point four)<br/><span><IMG width="225" height="234" src="https://app.oxbridge.es/app/movil/FT/Manual S1/Image_123.gif"/></span><br/>10. On which floor do you live? I live on the 4<span class="s23">th </span>floor. (fourth)<br/><span><IMG width="247" height="184" src="https://app.oxbridge.es/app/movil/FT/Manual S1/Image_124.jpg"/></span><br/>
  </p><p class="s13">ANSKING AND SAYING THE AGE. THE NUMBERS. FRACTIONS AND DECIMALS</p><p>11. When were you born? I was born on the 11<span class="s23">th </span>of October of 1982. (the eleventh of October of nineteen eighty-two).<br/><span><IMG width="192" height="200" src="https://app.oxbridge.es/app/movil/FT/Manual S1/Image_126.gif"/></span></p><p class="s24">ONLY FOR ADVANCED LEARNERS</p><p class="s13">ARITHMETIC</p><p class="s13">+ = addition                  6+4= 10 (six and four is ten)</p><p class="s13">- = substraction            6-4 = 2  (six minus four is two)</p><p class="s13">x = multiplication          6x4 = 24 (six multiplied by four is twenty-four)</p><p class="s13">/ = division                    4: 2 = 2 (four divided by two is two)</p><p class="s13">12.4 (twelve point four)</p><p class="s13">2/3 (two thirds), 4/5 (four fifths), 7/12 (seven over twelve)</p><p class="s13">22 (two squared), 43 (four cubed), 59 (five to the power of nine)</p><p class="s13">67% (sixty-seven per cent)</p><p class="s13">6 m x 10 m (six metres by ten metres)</p><p class="s13">My phone number is 70455. (seven o four double five) The city was founded in 1021. (ten twenty one) Shakespeare wrote Hamlet around 1600. (sixteen hundred) The company was established in 1901. (nineteen o one) Jack first visited Russia in 1993. (nineteen ninety-three)</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p class="s13">CALENDAR: DATES, DAYS, MONTHS, SEASONS, YEARS</p><p class="s15">Students: <span class="p">In English it is very useful to know how to express dates, days, months, seasons, and years. Here is a bit of information on the calendar:</span></p><p class="s15">The days of the week <span class="p">are: Monday, Tuesday, Wednesday, Thursday, Friday, Saturday and Sunday.</span></p><p><span><IMG width="246" height="246" src="https://app.oxbridge.es/app/movil/FT/Manual S1/Image_128.jpg"/></span></p><p class="s25">SUNDAY MONDAY TUESDAY WEDNESDAY THURSDAY FRIDAY SATURDAY</p><p><span><IMG width="395" height="290" src="https://app.oxbridge.es/app/movil/FT/Manual S1/Image_129.jpg"/></span></p><p class="s15">The months of the year <span class="p">are: January, February, March, April, May, June, July, August, September, October, November and December.</span></p><p>&nbsp;</p><p class="s13">CALENDAR: DATES, DAYS, MONTHS, SEASONS, YEARS</p><p class="s15">And the seasons <span class="p">are:</span></p><p>Spring             Summer              Autumn                Winter.<br/><span><IMG width="495" height="345" src="https://app.oxbridge.es/app/movil/FT/Manual S1/Image_131.jpg"/></span><br/>Here is a brief explanation on how dates are said in English. PLEASE pay attention to the order! <span class="s16">☺</span></p><p class="s15">ON + day <span class="p">(i.e. On Monday I am going to Paris.)</span></p><p class="s15">IN + Year <span class="p">(i.e. I was born in 1989.)</span></p><p class="s15">IN + the Morning / Afternoon / Evening / Season <span class="p">(i.e. In the morning I am going to the office.)</span></p><p>*NOTE: In English we express dates by using ordinal numbers (first, second, etc.) and we say the definite article &#39;the&#39;, but we don&#39;t write it. (Example: 11 Oct.<br/>1982 is pronounced: the eleventh of October of nineteen ninety nine). Here is the order of how to say dates:</p><p class="s15">Day – Month – Year <span class="p">// Eleventh October 1982</span></p><p>&nbsp;</p><p class="s13">CALENDAR: DATES, DAYS, MONTHS, SEASONS, YEARS</p><p>Here are some examples in use:<br/>1.  Days of the week:<br/>(a) On Monday I will go to the doctor’s.<br/><span><IMG width="190" height="187" src="https://app.oxbridge.es/app/movil/FT/Manual S1/Image_133.jpg"/></span><br/>(b) On Friday he has an exam.<br/><span><IMG width="253" height="190" src="https://app.oxbridge.es/app/movil/FT/Manual S1/Image_134.jpg"/></span><br/>2.  Months of the year:<br/>(a) We are in 2007.(two-thousand seven)<br/><span><IMG width="196" height="196" src="https://app.oxbridge.es/app/movil/FT/Manual S1/Image_135.png"/></span><br/>
  </p><p class="s13">CALENDAR: DATES, DAYS, MONTHS, SEASONS, YEARS</p><p>(b) The Barcelona Olympics were in 1992. (nineteen ninety-two)<br/><span><IMG width="238" height="238" src="https://app.oxbridge.es/app/movil/FT/Manual S1/Image_137.jpg"/></span><br/>3.  Seasons of the year:<br/>(a) In the summer we will go to Tenerife.<br/><span><IMG width="292" height="194" src="https://app.oxbridge.es/app/movil/FT/Manual S1/Image_138.jpg"/></span><br/>(b) In the afternoon they will have a coffee.<br/><span><IMG width="280" height="209" src="https://app.oxbridge.es/app/movil/FT/Manual S1/Image_139.jpg"/></span><br/>
  </p><p class="s13">CALENDAR: DATES, DAYS, MONTHS, SEASONS, YEARS</p><p>4.  Dates:<br/>(a) I was born on the 4<span class="s23">th </span>(fourth)  of July of 1995. (nineteen ninety-five)<br/><span><IMG width="217" height="217" src="https://app.oxbridge.es/app/movil/FT/Manual S1/Image_141.gif"/></span><br/>(b) We will go to Japan on the 7<span class="s23">th </span>(seventh) of August.<br/><span><IMG width="547" height="191" src="https://app.oxbridge.es/app/movil/FT/Manual S1/Image_142.png"/></span><br/>
  </p><p class="s13">SINGULAR AND PLURAL (REGULAR AND IRREGULAR PLURALS)</p><p>Students: The use of singular and plural nouns is very important and it is also very important to know how to say each. Please be aware that there are irregular nouns that in their singular and plural forms are a bit different in their format. In other words, irregular verbs usually means that you usually don’t add (-s) at the end of the noun, but change part of the structure.</p><p class="s15">SINGULAR: 1 object, concept or person</p><p class="s15">PLURAL: 2 or more objects, concepts or people</p><p class="s26">Structure:</p><p>1. Add an &quot;-s&quot;.<br/>Example: <b>cat---cats</b>. I have a <b>cat </b>and you have <b>3 cats</b>.<br/>2. Words ending with the SOUNDS &quot;ss&quot;, &quot;ch&quot;, &quot;x&quot; and &quot;sh&quot;, you add, &quot;-es&quot; Example: <b>watch---watches</b>. I have a Gucci watch and you have 3 Armani<br/>watches.<br/>3. Words ending &quot;CONSONANT + Y&quot; change to &quot;-ies&quot;.<br/>Example: <b>panty---panties</b>. She is wearing a nice panty, but she has a lot of nice panties.<br/>4. Words ending &quot;VOWEL + Y&quot; you add &quot;-s&quot;.<br/>Example: <b>bay---bays</b>. I live in a beautiful bay, but I like other bays, too.<br/>5. IRREGULAR PLURALS: No “-s” at the end!!! Remember:<br/>Example: <b>woman---women</b>. My friend is a wonderful woman. There are many great women in my life.</p><table border="1" cellspacing="0" style="border-collapse:collapse"><tr><td><p class="s27">Person---people</p></td><td><p class="s27">man---men   child---children</p></td><td><p class="s27">tooth---teeth</p></td></tr><tr><td><p class="s27">foot---feet</p></td><td><p class="s27">sheep---sheep</p></td><td/></tr></table><p>&nbsp;</p><p class="s13">SINGULAR AND PLURAL (REGULAR AND IRREGULAR PLURALS)</p><p>Look at the illustrated examples below:<br/>1. Add an &quot;-s&quot;.<br/>(a) Dog—Dogs. There is one dog. There are many dogs.<br/><span><IMG width="225" height="169" src="https://app.oxbridge.es/app/movil/FT/Manual S1/Image_145.jpg"/></span><br/>(b) Hat---Hats. He has a hat. He has many hats.<br/><span><IMG width="214" height="186" src="https://app.oxbridge.es/app/movil/FT/Manual S1/Image_146.jpg"/></span><br/>2. Words ending with the SOUNDS &quot;ss&quot;, &quot;ch&quot;, &quot;x&quot; and &quot;sh&quot;, you add, &quot;-es&quot; (a) Box---Boxes. I need a box. I need many boxes.<br/><span><IMG width="176" height="175" src="https://app.oxbridge.es/app/movil/FT/Manual S1/Image_147.gif"/></span><br/>
  </p><p class="s13">SINGULAR AND PLURAL (REGULAR AND IRREGULAR PLURALS)</p><p><span><IMG width="283" height="196" src="https://app.oxbridge.es/app/movil/FT/Manual S1/Image_149.jpg"/></span><br/>(b) Ass---Asses. I see an ass. I see many asses.</p><p class="s16">We love Catalonia! ☺</p><p>3. Words ending &quot;CONSONANT + Y&quot; change to &quot;-ies&quot;.<br/>(a) Family---Families. They have a family. There are many families.<br/><span><IMG width="256" height="204" src="https://app.oxbridge.es/app/movil/FT/Manual S1/Image_150.jpg"/></span><br/><span><IMG width="284" height="189" src="https://app.oxbridge.es/app/movil/FT/Manual S1/Image_151.png"/></span><br/>(b) Baby---Babies. They want a baby. We want many babies.<br/>Cute!<br/>
  </p><p class="s13">SINGULAR AND PLURAL (REGULAR AND IRREGULAR PLURALS)</p><p>4. Words ending &quot;VOWEL + Y&quot; you add &quot;-s&quot;.<br/>(a) Tray—Trays. He needs a tray. He needs many trays.<br/><span><IMG width="227" height="185" src="https://app.oxbridge.es/app/movil/FT/Manual S1/Image_153.jpg"/></span><br/>(b) Key---Keys. She has a key. She has many keys.<br/><span><IMG width="244" height="166" src="https://app.oxbridge.es/app/movil/FT/Manual S1/Image_154.gif"/></span><br/>5. IRREGULAR PLURALS:<br/>(a) Person---People. We see a person. We see many people.<br/><span><IMG width="298" height="206" src="https://app.oxbridge.es/app/movil/FT/Manual S1/Image_155.jpg"/></span><br/>
  </p><p class="s13">SINGULAR AND PLURAL (REGULAR AND IRREGULAR PLURALS)</p><p><span><IMG width="213" height="261" src="https://app.oxbridge.es/app/movil/FT/Manual S1/Image_157.jpg"/></span><br/>(b) Man---Men. I love my man. I love men.</p><p class="s16">My man, Brad ☺</p><p>(c) Child---Children. There is a child. There are many children.<br/><span><IMG width="256" height="183" src="https://app.oxbridge.es/app/movil/FT/Manual S1/Image_158.jpg"/></span><br/>(d) Tooth---Teeth. He has a tooth. He has teeth.<br/><span><IMG width="257" height="149" src="https://app.oxbridge.es/app/movil/FT/Manual S1/Image_159.jpg"/></span><br/>
  </p><p class="s13">SINGULAR AND PLURAL (REGULAR AND IRREGULAR PLURALS)</p><p>(e) Foot---Feet. I have a big foot. I have big feet.<br/><span><IMG width="295" height="232" src="https://app.oxbridge.es/app/movil/FT/Manual S1/Image_161.jpg"/></span><br/>(f) Sheep---Sheep. This is a Meryland sheep. There are many sheep.<br/><span><IMG width="263" height="198" src="https://app.oxbridge.es/app/movil/FT/Manual S1/Image_162.jpg"/></span><br/>
  </p><p class="s13">BASIC USE OF “SOME / ANY, HOW MUCH / HOW MANY”</p><p>Students: Please keep in mind that this structure is used to express quantity. We use <b>‘Some’ and ‘any’ </b>to speak about <b>indefinite quantities </b>(things/objects)<br/>or numbers, the exact quantity or number that we are thinking of is not important<br/>here.</p><p class="s15">’Some’ <span class="p">for affirmative statements</span></p><p class="s15">‘Any’ <span class="p">for questions and negative statements:</span></p><p>For example:           I need <b>some </b>sugar.<br/>She <b>doesn’t have any </b>clothes.</p><p class="s15">Does he have any <span class="p">pets? Also, </span>‘some’ <span class="p">can be used in questions.</span></p><p>For example:           Do you mind buying some bread for me?<br/>Should we bring some snacks?<br/>We use <b>‘how much’ </b>and <b>‘how many’ </b>for questions.</p><p class="s15">‘How much’ <span class="p">– in questions for things that are </span>not countable<span class="p">.</span></p><p class="s15">‘How many’ <span class="p">– In questions for things that are </span>countable<span class="p">.</span></p><p>For example:           <b>How much money </b>do you have?</p><p class="s15">How many brothers <span class="p">does he have? Here are more examples of the structure in use:</span></p><p>1.  Some / Any;<br/><span><IMG width="141" height="206" src="https://app.oxbridge.es/app/movil/FT/Manual S1/Image_164.jpg"/></span><br/>(a) There is some milk in the carton.</p><p class="s16">mmm…milk ☺</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p class="s13">BASIC USE OF “SOME / ANY, HOW MUCH / HOW MANY”</p><p>(b) We need some help to survive.<br/><span><IMG width="331" height="210" src="https://app.oxbridge.es/app/movil/FT/Manual S1/Image_166.jpg"/></span><br/>(c) We don’t have any chocolate.<br/><span><IMG width="279" height="266" src="https://app.oxbridge.es/app/movil/FT/Manual S1/Image_167.gif"/></span><br/>(d) They have no place to sleep. (= They don’t have any place to sleep.)<br/><span><IMG width="241" height="171" src="https://app.oxbridge.es/app/movil/FT/Manual S1/Image_168.jpg"/></span><br/>
  </p><p class="s13">BASIC USE OF “SOME / ANY, HOW MUCH / HOW MANY”</p><p>2.  Some / Any questions:<br/>(a) Does she have some salt?<br/><span><IMG width="150" height="228" src="https://app.oxbridge.es/app/movil/FT/Manual S1/Image_170.jpg"/></span><br/><span><IMG width="396" height="222" src="https://app.oxbridge.es/app/movil/FT/Manual S1/Image_171.png"/></span><br/>(b) Shall we drink some tequila?</p><p class="s16">Salt, tequila, and lemon, party! ☺</p><p>(c) Is there any Chinese food left?<br/><span><IMG width="229" height="194" src="https://app.oxbridge.es/app/movil/FT/Manual S1/Image_172.png"/></span><br/>
  </p><p class="s13">BASIC USE OF “SOME / ANY, HOW MUCH / HOW MANY”</p><p>Yummy!<br/>3.  How much…? / How many…?:<br/>(a) How much water is there?</p><p class="s16">Can I have some water?</p><p class="s16">☺</p><p><span><IMG width="366" height="396" src="https://app.oxbridge.es/app/movil/FT/Manual S1/Image_174.png"/></span><br/>(b) How many kisses do you want?<br/><span><IMG width="428" height="295" src="https://app.oxbridge.es/app/movil/FT/Manual S1/Image_175.jpg"/></span><br/>
  </p><p class="s13">BASIC USE OF “SOME / ANY, HOW MUCH / HOW MANY”</p><p>(c) How much do you love your boyfriend?<br/><span><IMG width="274" height="335" src="https://app.oxbridge.es/app/movil/FT/Manual S1/Image_177.gif"/></span><br/><span><IMG width="234" height="334" src="https://app.oxbridge.es/app/movil/FT/Manual S1/Image_178.jpg"/></span><br/>(d) How many presents do you have?<br/>I love presents! <span class="s16">☺</span><br/>
  </p><p class="s13">EXPRESSING POSSESSIONS: POSSESSIVE ADJECTIVES AND POSSESSIVE PRONOUNS</p><p>Students: This is a very simple English grammar structure, but it is also very important.<br/>There is only one form for singular or plural, male or female (except: <b>he</b>, <b>she </b>&amp;</p><p class="s15">it<span class="p">).</span></p><p>1. In English we use the <b>possessive adjectives before nouns </b>to say who they belong to.<br/>For example:<br/>I have a dog.                      <b>My </b>dog is big.<br/>He has a girlfriend.             <b>His </b>girlfriend is beautiful. They have a family.            <b>Their </b>family is very big.<br/>2. <b>&quot;Possessive pronouns&quot;</b>: they substitute the noun while expressing possession. Possessive pronouns are generally after &quot;It&#39;s/they are&quot;.<br/>For example:           This is <b>my </b>bag. The bag is <b>mine </b>/ it’s <b>mine.</b><br/><span><IMG width="72" height="40" src="https://app.oxbridge.es/app/movil/FT/Manual S1/Image_180.png"/></span><br/><span><IMG width="85" height="40" src="https://app.oxbridge.es/app/movil/FT/Manual S1/Image_181.png"/></span><br/><span><IMG width="91" height="40" src="https://app.oxbridge.es/app/movil/FT/Manual S1/Image_182.png"/></span><br/><span><IMG width="71" height="40" src="https://app.oxbridge.es/app/movil/FT/Manual S1/Image_183.png"/></span><br/><span><IMG width="85" height="40" src="https://app.oxbridge.es/app/movil/FT/Manual S1/Image_184.png"/></span><br/><span><IMG width="91" height="40" src="https://app.oxbridge.es/app/movil/FT/Manual S1/Image_185.png"/></span><br/><span><IMG width="71" height="40" src="https://app.oxbridge.es/app/movil/FT/Manual S1/Image_186.png"/></span><br/><span><IMG width="84" height="40" src="https://app.oxbridge.es/app/movil/FT/Manual S1/Image_187.png"/></span><br/><span><IMG width="90" height="40" src="https://app.oxbridge.es/app/movil/FT/Manual S1/Image_188.png"/></span><br/><span><IMG width="72" height="40" src="https://app.oxbridge.es/app/movil/FT/Manual S1/Image_189.png"/></span><br/><span><IMG width="85" height="40" src="https://app.oxbridge.es/app/movil/FT/Manual S1/Image_190.png"/></span><br/><span><IMG width="91" height="40" src="https://app.oxbridge.es/app/movil/FT/Manual S1/Image_191.png"/></span><br/><span><IMG width="72" height="40" src="https://app.oxbridge.es/app/movil/FT/Manual S1/Image_192.png"/></span><br/><span><IMG width="85" height="40" src="https://app.oxbridge.es/app/movil/FT/Manual S1/Image_193.png"/></span><br/><span><IMG width="91" height="40" src="https://app.oxbridge.es/app/movil/FT/Manual S1/Image_194.png"/></span><br/><span><IMG width="72" height="40" src="https://app.oxbridge.es/app/movil/FT/Manual S1/Image_195.png"/></span><br/><span><IMG width="85" height="40" src="https://app.oxbridge.es/app/movil/FT/Manual S1/Image_196.png"/></span><br/><span><IMG width="91" height="40" src="https://app.oxbridge.es/app/movil/FT/Manual S1/Image_197.png"/></span><br/><span><IMG width="70" height="39" src="https://app.oxbridge.es/app/movil/FT/Manual S1/Image_198.png"/></span><br/><span><IMG width="84" height="39" src="https://app.oxbridge.es/app/movil/FT/Manual S1/Image_199.png"/></span><br/><span><IMG width="89" height="39" src="https://app.oxbridge.es/app/movil/FT/Manual S1/Image_200.png"/></span><br/>Here is a list of all the Possessive Adjectives and Possessive Pronouns:</p><table border="1" cellspacing="0" style="border-collapse:collapse"><tr><td><p class="s28">Person</p></td><td/><td><p class="s28">Pronoun</p></td><td/><td><p class="s28">Adjective</p></td></tr><tr><td><p class="s29">I</p></td><td/><td><p class="s29">mine</p></td><td/><td><p class="s29">my</p></td></tr><tr><td><p class="s29">You</p></td><td/><td><p class="s29">yours</p></td><td/><td><p class="s29">your</p></td></tr><tr><td><p class="s29">She</p></td><td/><td><p class="s29">hers</p></td><td/><td><p class="s29">her</p></td></tr><tr><td><p class="s29">He</p></td><td/><td><p class="s29">his</p></td><td/><td><p class="s29">his</p></td></tr><tr><td><p class="s29">It</p></td><td/><td><p class="s29">its</p></td><td/><td><p class="s29">its</p></td></tr><tr><td><p class="s29">We</p></td><td/><td><p class="s29">ours</p></td><td/><td><p class="s29">our</p></td></tr><tr><td><p class="s29">They</p></td><td/><td><p class="s29">theirs</p></td><td/><td><p class="s29">their</p></td></tr></table><p>&nbsp;</p><p class="s13">EXPRESSING POSSESSIONS: POSSESSIVE ADJECTIVES AND POSSESSIVE PRONOUNS</p><p>Here are some examples in use:<br/>(a) This is my dog. / That dog is mine.<br/><span><IMG width="268" height="201" src="https://app.oxbridge.es/app/movil/FT/Manual S1/Image_202.jpg"/></span><br/>(b) This is your brother. (adj.) / He is yours. (pro.)<br/><span><IMG width="213" height="191" src="https://app.oxbridge.es/app/movil/FT/Manual S1/Image_203.jpg"/></span><br/>(c) This is her/his lunch bag. (adj.) / That lunch bag is hers/his. (pro.)<br/><span><IMG width="227" height="227" src="https://app.oxbridge.es/app/movil/FT/Manual S1/Image_204.jpg"/></span><br/>
  </p><p class="s13">EXPRESSING POSSESSIONS: POSSESSIVE ADJECTIVES AND POSSESSIVE PRONOUNS</p><p>(d) The dog has a tail. / That tail is <b>its </b>(pro.) / I<b>ts </b>tail is large. (pro.)<br/>Look at my tail!<br/><span><IMG width="250" height="245" src="https://app.oxbridge.es/app/movil/FT/Manual S1/Image_206.png"/></span><br/>(e) It is our car. (adj.) / That car is ours. (pro.<br/><span><IMG width="242" height="182" src="https://app.oxbridge.es/app/movil/FT/Manual S1/Image_207.jpg"/></span><br/>(f)  It is their house. (adj.) / That house is theirs. (pro.)<br/><span><IMG width="288" height="216" src="https://app.oxbridge.es/app/movil/FT/Manual S1/Image_208.jpg"/></span><br/>
  </p><p class="s13">EXPRESSING POSESSIONS: “HAVE / HAVE GOT”</p><p class="s14">Students<span class="p">: We use “have” and &quot;have got&quot; to talk about possession (ours or others).</span></p><p class="s15">“Have got” = “have”</p><p>We use &quot;Have got&quot; in affirmative if it is true that you or someone else possesses something. So, we use &quot;haven’t got&quot; when we or someone else does not possess something. Finally, we use &quot;have got&quot; in questions and short answers to ask if someone posses something.<br/>Here you have all of the forms of ‘HAVE’, please a take a look at them:</p><p class="s30">HAVE                                            HAVE GOT</p><p>Learn this first!<br/><span><IMG width="44" height="25" src="https://app.oxbridge.es/app/movil/FT/Manual S1/Image_210.png"/></span></p><table border="1" cellspacing="0" style="border-collapse:collapse"><tr><td><p class="s27">AFFIRMATIVE ‘HAVE’:</p><p class="s19">- I have</p><p class="s19">- You have</p><p class="s19">- They have. We have</p><p class="s19">- He/she/it <b>has</b></p></td><td><p class="s27">AFFIRMATIVE ‘HAVE GOT’:</p><p class="s19">-    I have got (I&#39;ve got)</p><p class="s19">-    You have got (You&#39;ve got)</p><p class="s19">-    They/We have got (They&#39;ve got)</p><p class="s19">-    He/she/it <b>has </b>got (He/she/it&#39;s got)</p></td></tr><tr><td><p class="s27">NEGATIVE ‘HAVE’:</p><p class="s19">- I don’t have</p><p class="s19">- You don’t have</p><p class="s19">- He/she/ it <b>doesn’t  have</b></p><p class="s19">- We don’t have</p><p class="s19">- They don’t have</p></td><td><p class="s27">NEGATIVE ‘HAVEN’T GOT’:</p><p class="s19">-    I have not got (I haven&#39;t got)</p><p class="s19">-    You have not got (you haven&#39;t got)</p><p class="s19">-    He/she/it has not got (He/she/it hasn&#39;t got)</p><p class="s19">-    We have not got (we haven&#39;t got)</p><p class="s19">-    They have not got (they haven&#39;t got)</p></td></tr><tr><td><p class="s27">‘HAVE’ QUESTION / SHORT ANSWER:</p><p class="s19">- Do I have? – Yes, you do./ No, you don’t.</p><p class="s19">- Do you have? – Yes, I do. / No, I</p><p class="s19">don’t.</p><p class="s19">- <b>Does </b>he/she/it <b>have</b>? – Yes, he/she/it does. / No, <b>he/she/it doesn’t</b></p><p class="s19">- Do we have? – No, we don’t</p><p class="s19">- Do they have? – No, they don’t</p></td><td><p class="s27">‘HAVE GOT’ QUESTION / SHORT ANSWER:</p><p class="s19">-    Have I got? Yes, you have / No, you haven&#39;t</p><p class="s19">-    Have you got? Yes, I have / No, I</p><p class="s19">haven&#39;t</p><p class="s19">-    Has he/she/it got? Yes, he/she/it has-- No, he/she/it hasn&#39;t</p><p class="s19">-    Have we got? Yes, we have / no, we haven&#39;t</p><p class="s19">-    Have they got? Yes, they have/ No, they haven&#39;t</p></td></tr></table><p>&nbsp;</p><p class="s13">EXPRESSING POSESSIONS: “HAVE / HAVE GOT”</p><p class="s15">HERE ARE SOME EXAMPLES IN USE:</p><p class="s15">1.  ‘HAVE GOT’ AND ‘HAVE’:</p><p><span><IMG width="351" height="178" src="https://app.oxbridge.es/app/movil/FT/Manual S1/Image_212.png"/></span><br/>(a) I have got a new cat. / I have a new cat.</p><p class="s16">I am so cute ☺</p><p><span><IMG width="244" height="212" src="https://app.oxbridge.es/app/movil/FT/Manual S1/Image_213.png"/></span><br/>(b) He has got a new girlfriend. / He has a new girlfriend.</p><p class="s16">I love you.</p><p><span><IMG width="285" height="224" src="https://app.oxbridge.es/app/movil/FT/Manual S1/Image_214.png"/></span><br/>(c) You have got a great body. / You have a great body.</p><p class="s16">Thank you.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p class="s13">EXPRESSING POSESSIONS: “HAVE / HAVE GOT”</p><p class="s15">2.  ‘HAVEN’T GOT’ and ‘’HAVE’:</p><p><span><IMG width="387" height="298" src="https://app.oxbridge.es/app/movil/FT/Manual S1/Image_216.png"/></span><br/>(a) We haven’t got money. / We don’t have any money.</p><p class="s16">I have money from the Spanish people.</p><p><span><IMG width="402" height="325" src="https://app.oxbridge.es/app/movil/FT/Manual S1/Image_217.png"/></span><br/>(b) They haven’t got the time. / They don’t have the time.</p><p class="s16">What’s the time?</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p class="s13">EXPRESSING POSESSIONS: “HAVE / HAVE GOT”</p><p>(c) She hasn’t got nice clothes. / She doesn’t have nice clothes.</p><p class="s16">I know!!!!</p><p><span><IMG width="541" height="339" src="https://app.oxbridge.es/app/movil/FT/Manual S1/Image_219.png"/></span><br/>(Paris Hilton)</p><p class="s15">3.  ‘HAVE GOT’ and ‘HAVE’ QUESTIONS / SHORT ANSWERS:</p><p><span><IMG width="424" height="254" src="https://app.oxbridge.es/app/movil/FT/Manual S1/Image_220.png"/></span><br/>(a) Have you got some sugar? Yes, I have. / No, I haven’t. / Do you have some sugar? Yes, I do. / No, I don’t.</p><p class="s16">Here is your sugar.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p class="s13">EXPRESSING POSESSIONS: “HAVE / HAVE GOT”</p><p><span><IMG width="424" height="386" src="https://app.oxbridge.es/app/movil/FT/Manual S1/Image_222.png"/></span><br/>(b) Have we got the concert tickets? Yes, we have. / No, we haven’t. / Do we have the concert tickets? Yes, we do. / No, we don’t.</p><p class="s16">We are going to see</p><p class="s16">Chenoa in concert ☺</p><p>(c) Have I got a handsome boyfriend? Yes, you have. / No, you haven’t. /<br/><span><IMG width="478" height="264" src="https://app.oxbridge.es/app/movil/FT/Manual S1/Image_223.png"/></span><br/>Do I have a handsome boyfriend? Yes, you do. / No, you don’t.</p><p class="s16">And he is also intelligent, caring and…</p><p class="s16">…mine! ☺</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p class="s13">EXPRESSING POSESSIONS: THE SAXON GENITIVE</p><p class="s14">Students<span class="p">: Here is another important structure that deals with personal possession---the Saxon genitive. It says that something belongs to somebody</span></p><p><span><IMG width="345" height="184" src="https://app.oxbridge.es/app/movil/FT/Manual S1/Image_225.png"/></span><br/>Mary has a phone. This is <b>the phone of </b>Mary. This is <b>Mary’s phone</b>.<br/>I am Mary’s phone<br/>We use the Saxon genitive when we want to talk about:<br/>1. <b>A person + a thing</b><br/>Ex. It&#39;s <b>my mother&#39;s ring</b>. (The ring of my mother)<br/>2. <b>A person + a person</b><br/>Ex. He&#39;s <b>my sister’s boyfriend</b>. (The boyfriend of my sister)<br/><span><IMG width="153" height="36" src="https://app.oxbridge.es/app/movil/FT/Manual S1/Image_226.png"/></span><br/>3. <b>Don&#39;t use it for thing + thing</b><br/>Ex. The end of the film. (<b>NOT: </b>The film&#39;s end.<span class="s16">-7</span>wrong!!!)</p><p class="s15">4. For plurals and when a noun finishes in &quot;s&quot; the comma goes at the end but we pronounce “-iz”.</p><p>Ex.     These are Jess&#39; journals. (The journals of Jess) Here Jess’ is pronounced <i>“Jessiz”</i><br/>Now, here you have some more illustrated examples of the Saxon genitive. Please make sure you look carefully at each one to see how the structure is used and when it is not used.<br/>1. <b>A person + a thing</b><br/>(a) My father’s father died.<br/><span><IMG width="112" height="138" src="https://app.oxbridge.es/app/movil/FT/Manual S1/Image_227.jpg"/></span><br/>
  </p><p class="s13">EXPRESSING POSESSIONS: THE SAXON GENITIVE</p><p><span><IMG width="285" height="198" src="https://app.oxbridge.es/app/movil/FT/Manual S1/Image_229.png"/></span><br/>(b) The President’s wife is angry.</p><p class="s16">I have a problem!</p><p>2. <b>A person + a person</b><br/>(a) My grandma is my mother’s mother.</p><p class="s16">I am not so old!</p><p><span><IMG width="256" height="216" src="https://app.oxbridge.es/app/movil/FT/Manual S1/Image_230.png"/></span><br/><span><IMG width="289" height="215" src="https://app.oxbridge.es/app/movil/FT/Manual S1/Image_231.png"/></span><br/>(b) This is Paul and this is Paul’s brother.<br/>I’m Paul<br/>
  </p><p class="s13">EXPRESSING POSESSIONS: THE SAXON GENITIVE</p><p>3. <b>Don&#39;t use it for thing + thing</b><br/><span><IMG width="153" height="36" src="https://app.oxbridge.es/app/movil/FT/Manual S1/Image_233.png"/></span><br/>(a) That is the cap of the bottle. (The cap’s bottle <span class="s16">-7 </span>wrong!!)<br/><span><IMG width="115" height="115" src="https://app.oxbridge.es/app/movil/FT/Manual S1/Image_234.jpg"/></span><br/>(b) The ball of the game.<br/><span><IMG width="113" height="123" src="https://app.oxbridge.es/app/movil/FT/Manual S1/Image_235.jpg"/></span><br/>4. <b>When a noun finishes in &quot;s&quot; the comma goes at the end</b><br/>(a) They are Alexis’ (“<i>Alexisiz”) </i>pets.<br/><span><IMG width="253" height="141" src="https://app.oxbridge.es/app/movil/FT/Manual S1/Image_236.jpg"/></span><br/>(b) We love the Tomas’ <i>(“Tomasiz”) </i>new toys.<br/><span><IMG width="318" height="173" src="https://app.oxbridge.es/app/movil/FT/Manual S1/Image_237.jpg"/></span><br/>
  </p><p class="s13">THE PRESENT SIMPLE TENSE IN AFFIRMATIVE, INTERROGATIVE AND NEGATIVE FORMS</p><p class="s14">Students<span class="p">: First, beware that in English we use the present simple to talk about</span></p><p><span><IMG width="306" height="265" src="https://app.oxbridge.es/app/movil/FT/Manual S1/Image_239.jpg"/></span><br/>CUSTOMS, HABITS, and ROUTINES and to talk about FREQUENCY. Example:      The Spanish have dinner at 9:30 PM.<br/>The structure of the present simple is the same for all ‘people’ <b>except </b>the THIRD PERSON SINGULAR (he/she/it). We form the third person singular in verbs by ADDING &quot;s&quot; to most of them.</p><p class="s15">Remember and learn:</p><p>FORM: The same for all “people”, except <b>she, he, it: we add “–s” to the verb.</b><br/>USE: For <b>habits, routines, frequency.</b><br/>Examples:<br/><span><IMG width="129" height="184" src="https://app.oxbridge.es/app/movil/FT/Manual S1/Image_240.jpg"/></span><br/>Drink- drinks (<b>I drink </b>Coca-cola. ---<b>He drinks </b>Fanta),<br/><span><IMG width="118" height="192" src="https://app.oxbridge.es/app/movil/FT/Manual S1/Image_241.jpg"/></span><br/>
  </p><p class="s13">THE PRESENT SIMPLE TENSE IN AFFIRMATIVE, INTERROGATIVE AND NEGATIVE FORMS</p><p>Eat-eats (<b>We eat </b>grilled cheese sandwiches. ---<b>She eats </b>tuna fish sandwiches),<br/><span><IMG width="168" height="168" src="https://app.oxbridge.es/app/movil/FT/Manual S1/Image_243.jpg"/></span><br/><span><IMG width="166" height="174" src="https://app.oxbridge.es/app/movil/FT/Manual S1/Image_244.jpg"/></span><br/>Swim- swims (They always swim. ---It always swims.)<br/><span><IMG width="301" height="174" src="https://app.oxbridge.es/app/movil/FT/Manual S1/Image_245.jpg"/></span></p><p class="s14">Questions<span class="p">: For questions we start with DO or DOES (for he, she, it) + person +</span></p><p>verb (and we add <b>no “-s”</b>)</p><table border="1" cellspacing="0" style="border-collapse:collapse"><tr><td><p class="s31">-    <span class="s19">DO you swim?</span></p><p class="s19">swim?</p></td><td><p class="s19">- DOES he swim (no “-s”)?</p></td><td><p class="s19">- DO we</p></td></tr><tr><td><p class="s31">-    <span class="s19">Yes, I do.</span></p><p class="s31">-    <span class="s19">No, I don’t.</span></p></td><td><p class="s19">- Yes, he does.</p><p class="s19">- No, he doesn’t.</p></td><td><p class="s19">- Yes, we do.</p><p class="s19">- No, we don’t.</p></td></tr></table><p class="s15"><u>Negative forms:</u> <span class="p">For negatives we add DO NOT (DON’T) for all people or DOES NOT (DOESN’T) for </span>he, she, it and <span class="p">we add </span>no “-s”</p><p class="s15">.</p><p class="s15">Person + DON’T/DOESN’T + verb.</p><p>I do not (don’t) swim.      You don’t eat.   He <b>doesn’t </b>smoke.     We don’t drink.<br/>
  </p><p class="s13">THE PRESENT SIMPLE TENSE IN AFFIRMATIVE, INTERROGATIVE AND NEGATIVE FORMS</p><p>Please note that you need to add &quot;-es&quot; to DO and GO and verbs that end in -ch, - ss, -sh and –x.<br/>Examples:     Do-does (Do you swim?—Does it swim?)<br/><span><IMG width="229" height="168" src="https://app.oxbridge.es/app/movil/FT/Manual S1/Image_247.jpg"/></span><br/>Go-goes (I go to school. ---He goes to school)<br/><span><IMG width="183" height="222" src="https://app.oxbridge.es/app/movil/FT/Manual S1/Image_248.gif"/></span><br/>Watch-watches (I watch TV. ---He watches TV)<br/><span><IMG width="300" height="225" src="https://app.oxbridge.es/app/movil/FT/Manual S1/Image_249.jpg"/></span><br/>
  </p><p class="s13">THE PRESENT SIMPLE TENSE IN AFFIRMATIVE, INTERROGATIVE AND NEGATIVE FORMS</p><p>Also, we DROP (eliminate) the -y and ADD -ies to verbs that end in CONSONANT<br/>+ -Y<br/>Examples:     Carry-carries (I always carry my books. ---She always carries her books)<br/><span><IMG width="177" height="277" src="https://app.oxbridge.es/app/movil/FT/Manual S1/Image_251.gif"/></span><br/>Cry-cries (We always cry. ---The baby always cries.)<br/><span><IMG width="435" height="291" src="https://app.oxbridge.es/app/movil/FT/Manual S1/Image_252.jpg"/></span><br/>
  </p><p class="s13">THE PRESENT SIMPLE TENSE IN AFFIRMATIVE, INTERROGATIVE AND NEGATIVE FORMS</p><p class="s15">Examples with negative statements:</p><p>Americans don’t eat healthy food<br/><span><IMG width="158" height="228" src="https://app.oxbridge.es/app/movil/FT/Manual S1/Image_254.jpg"/></span><br/>We don’t eat cookies.<br/><span><IMG width="160" height="169" src="https://app.oxbridge.es/app/movil/FT/Manual S1/Image_255.jpg"/></span><br/>My dog doesn’t like people.<br/><span><IMG width="153" height="208" src="https://app.oxbridge.es/app/movil/FT/Manual S1/Image_256.jpg"/></span><br/>
  </p><p class="s13">THE PRESENT SIMPLE TENSE IN AFFIRMATIVE, INTERROGATIVE AND NEGATIVE FORMS</p><p>She/he doesn’t eat fish.<br/><span><IMG width="291" height="198" src="https://app.oxbridge.es/app/movil/FT/Manual S1/Image_258.gif"/></span></p><p class="s15">Examples with questions:</p><p>Do you play football on Sunday? Yes, I do. / No, I don&#39;t<br/><span><IMG width="577" height="190" src="https://app.oxbridge.es/app/movil/FT/Manual S1/Image_259.png"/></span><br/>Do they live in Sitges? Yes, they do. / No, they don&#39;t<br/><span><IMG width="270" height="177" src="https://app.oxbridge.es/app/movil/FT/Manual S1/Image_260.jpg"/></span><br/>
  </p><p class="s13">THE PRESENT SIMPLE TENSE IN AFFIRMATIVE, INTERROGATIVE AND NEGATIVE FORMS</p><p>Does he play badminton on Sunday? Yes, he does. / No, he doesn&#39;t.<br/><span><IMG width="145" height="228" src="https://app.oxbridge.es/app/movil/FT/Manual S1/Image_262.jpg"/></span><br/>Does she live in Badalona? Yes, she does. / No, she doesn&#39;t<br/><span><IMG width="287" height="312" src="https://app.oxbridge.es/app/movil/FT/Manual S1/Image_263.jpg"/></span><br/>
  </p><p class="s13">MOST COMMON PREPOSITIONS OF PLACE: IN ON AT TO INTO</p><p>Students: In English we use this structure to indicate the <b>location </b>of something or someone. Some of the most common prepositions of place are: IN, ON, AT, TO, and INTO. Please be aware that each has it use; it all depends on the location of the person or thing.<br/>Remember the <b>cat </b>and the <b>boxes</b><br/><span><IMG width="86" height="110" src="https://app.oxbridge.es/app/movil/FT/Manual S1/Image_265.png"/></span></p><p class="s15">THE CAT IS…</p><p><span><IMG width="99" height="78" src="https://app.oxbridge.es/app/movil/FT/Manual S1/Image_266.png"/></span><br/><span><IMG width="107" height="83" src="https://app.oxbridge.es/app/movil/FT/Manual S1/Image_267.png"/></span><br/><span><IMG width="100" height="67" src="https://app.oxbridge.es/app/movil/FT/Manual S1/Image_268.png"/></span><br/><span><IMG width="3" height="1" src="https://app.oxbridge.es/app/movil/FT/Manual S1/Image_269.jpg"/></span></p><p class="s32">… <b>behind </b>the box         …<b>on </b>the box                 …<b>in front of </b>the box                …<b>in </b>the box</p><p><span><IMG width="112" height="92" src="https://app.oxbridge.es/app/movil/FT/Manual S1/Image_270.png"/></span><br/><span><IMG width="103" height="68" src="https://app.oxbridge.es/app/movil/FT/Manual S1/Image_271.png"/></span><br/><span><IMG width="86" height="67" src="https://app.oxbridge.es/app/movil/FT/Manual S1/Image_272.png"/></span><br/><span><IMG width="43" height="53" src="https://app.oxbridge.es/app/movil/FT/Manual S1/Image_273.png"/></span><br/><span><IMG width="140" height="70" src="https://app.oxbridge.es/app/movil/FT/Manual S1/Image_274.png"/></span></p><p class="s32">… <b>under </b>the box               … <b>next to </b>the box       … <b>near </b>the box                          <b>… between </b>the boxes</p><p>Here is a brief and useful summary of each:<br/>1)  <b>IN</b><br/>In English we use “in” when we want to say that something or someone is in an enclosed place, or figuratively speaking.<br/>For example:<br/>Do you work <b>in </b>an office?<br/><span><IMG width="213" height="142" src="https://app.oxbridge.es/app/movil/FT/Manual S1/Image_275.png"/></span><br/>
  </p><p class="s13">MOST COMMON PREPOSITIONS OF PLACE: IN ON AT TO INTO</p><p>I have a meeting <b>in </b>New York.<br/><span><IMG width="309" height="232" src="https://app.oxbridge.es/app/movil/FT/Manual S1/Image_277.png"/></span><br/>He is <b>in </b>a box.<br/><span><IMG width="244" height="184" src="https://app.oxbridge.es/app/movil/FT/Manual S1/Image_278.png"/></span><br/>2)  <b>AT</b><br/>In English we use &#39;at&#39; with places and for a point/location.<br/>For example:<br/>Jane is <b>at </b>the bus stop.<br/><span><IMG width="105" height="163" src="https://app.oxbridge.es/app/movil/FT/Manual S1/Image_279.gif"/></span><br/>
  </p><p class="s13">MOST COMMON PREPOSITIONS OF PLACE: IN ON AT TO INTO</p><p>The shop is <b>at </b>the end of the street.<br/><span><IMG width="148" height="198" src="https://app.oxbridge.es/app/movil/FT/Manual S1/Image_281.png"/></span><br/>When do you arrive <b>at </b>the office?<br/><span><IMG width="115" height="174" src="https://app.oxbridge.es/app/movil/FT/Manual S1/Image_282.jpg"/></span><br/>3)  <b>ON</b><br/>We use &#39;on&#39; with surfaces and directions. For example:<br/>His name is <b>on </b>the tag.<br/><span><IMG width="167" height="167" src="https://app.oxbridge.es/app/movil/FT/Manual S1/Image_283.jpg"/></span><br/>
  </p><p class="s13">MOST COMMON PREPOSITIONS OF PLACE: IN ON AT TO INTO</p><p>You are standing <b>on </b>my foot.<br/><span><IMG width="166" height="212" src="https://app.oxbridge.es/app/movil/FT/Manual S1/Image_285.jpg"/></span><br/>I live <b>on </b>the 4th floor <b>at </b>Mistral Avenue <b>in </b>Barcelona.<br/><span><IMG width="150" height="150" src="https://app.oxbridge.es/app/movil/FT/Manual S1/Image_286.gif"/></span></p><p class="s15">4)  TO</p><p class="s15">We use <span class="p">to talk about orientation towards a goal. When the goal is physical, such as a destination, &quot;to&quot; implies movement in the direction of</span></p><p>the     goal.<br/>For example:<br/>He goes <b>to </b>his house.<br/><span><IMG width="225" height="118" src="https://app.oxbridge.es/app/movil/FT/Manual S1/Image_287.gif"/></span><br/>
  </p><p class="s13">MOST COMMON PREPOSITIONS OF PLACE: IN ON AT TO INTO</p><p>When the goal is not a physical place, for instance, an action, &quot;to&quot; expresses purpose.<br/>For example:<br/>It takes a shower <b>to </b>feel clean.<br/><span><IMG width="253" height="191" src="https://app.oxbridge.es/app/movil/FT/Manual S1/Image_289.jpg"/></span></p><p class="s15">5)  INTO (inside)</p><p>We use ‘into’ to state when something/someone is going inside something else, or when something becomes something else, or when something hits something        else.<br/>For example:<br/>They run <b>into </b>one another.<br/><span><IMG width="200" height="263" src="https://app.oxbridge.es/app/movil/FT/Manual S1/Image_290.jpg"/></span><br/>
  </p><p class="s13">MOST COMMON PREPOSITIONS OF PLACE: IN ON AT TO INTO</p><p>She turns <b>into </b>a mouse.<br/><span><IMG width="329" height="416" src="https://app.oxbridge.es/app/movil/FT/Manual S1/Image_292.png"/></span><br/>Put the fruit <b>into </b>the basket.<br/><span><IMG width="159" height="242" src="https://app.oxbridge.es/app/movil/FT/Manual S1/Image_293.jpg"/></span><br/>
  </p><p class="s13">MOST COMMON PREPOSITIONS OF PLACE: IN ON AT TO INTO</p><p>6)  <b>IMPORTANT NOTES</b></p><p class="s15">---<span class="p">In / at / on the corner</span></p><p>We say &#39;in the corner of a room&#39;, but &#39;at the corner (or &#39;on the corner&#39;) of a street&#39;<br/>---In / at / on the front<br/>We say &#39;in the front / in the back&#39; of a car<br/>We say &#39;at the front / at the back&#39; of buildings / groups of people<br/>We say &#39;on the front / on the back&#39; of a piece of paper<br/>
  </p><p class="s13">THE PRESENT CONTINUOUS TENSE FOR ACTIONS IN PROGRESS AND COMPLAINTS</p><p><u><b>Students</b></u>: Here you have another important structure, but this structure is for expressing <b>actions in progress </b>and complaints.<br/>Here is the form:</p><p class="s15">AFFIRMATIVE: S + to be + V + ing NEGATIVE: S + to be + not + V + ing INTERROGATIVE: To be + S + V + ing?</p><p class="s15">SHORT ANSWERS: Yes, I am / No, I’m not etc…</p><p>Please note that we use the present continuous to talk about an action that’s<br/>IN PROGRESS now, at this moment.<br/>For example:           Bob is making dinner for his family.<br/><span><IMG width="161" height="245" src="https://app.oxbridge.es/app/movil/FT/Manual S1/Image_296.jpg"/></span><br/>We are making a cake.<br/><span><IMG width="213" height="198" src="https://app.oxbridge.es/app/movil/FT/Manual S1/Image_297.gif"/></span><br/>
  </p><p class="s13">THE PRESENT CONTINUOUS TENSE FOR ACTIONS IN PROGRESS AND COMPLAINTS</p><p>What are you doing now? // Are you making spaghetti. // I’m making spaghetti.<br/><span><IMG width="199" height="242" src="https://app.oxbridge.es/app/movil/FT/Manual S1/Image_299.jpg"/></span><br/>What is he doing? // Is he playing? // He is playing PlayStation.<br/><span><IMG width="271" height="204" src="https://app.oxbridge.es/app/movil/FT/Manual S1/Image_300.jpg"/></span><br/>She is not reading a book.<br/><span><IMG width="188" height="223" src="https://app.oxbridge.es/app/movil/FT/Manual S1/Image_301.jpg"/></span><br/>
  </p><p class="s13">THE PRESENT CONTINUOUS TENSE FOR ACTIONS IN PROGRESS AND COMPLAINTS</p><p>We are not laughing.<br/><span><IMG width="324" height="196" src="https://app.oxbridge.es/app/movil/FT/Manual S1/Image_303.jpg"/></span><br/>Here you have some verbs that are <b>NOT </b>used in the continuous: WANT, NEED, PREFER, LIKE, LOVE, HATE, BELONG, SEE, HEAR,<br/>KNOW, REALISE, BELIEVE, SUPPOSE, MEAN UNDERSTAND, REMEMBER, FORGET, SEEM.<br/>In order to express complaints, we use the same format as above, but we add<br/>‘<b>ALWAYS</b>’.<br/>Here is the format:</p><p class="s15">S + to be + always + V + ing + C</p><p class="s15">INTERROGATIVE: To be + S + always + V + ing + C? SHORT ANSWERS: Yes, I am / No, I’m not etc…</p><p>Here are some examples:<br/><span><IMG width="165" height="190" src="https://app.oxbridge.es/app/movil/FT/Manual S1/Image_304.jpg"/></span><br/>She is always smoking.<br/>I love to smoke <span class="s16">☺</span><br/>
  </p><p class="s13">THE PRESENT CONTINUOUS TENSE FOR ACTIONS IN PROGRESS AND COMPLAINTS</p><p>He is always snoring.<br/><span><IMG width="250" height="189" src="https://app.oxbridge.es/app/movil/FT/Manual S1/Image_306.jpg"/></span><br/>They are always eating fast food.<br/><span><IMG width="320" height="224" src="https://app.oxbridge.es/app/movil/FT/Manual S1/Image_307.jpg"/></span><br/><span><IMG width="279" height="233" src="https://app.oxbridge.es/app/movil/FT/Manual S1/Image_308.jpg"/></span><br/>Is it always chewing? Yes, it is. / No, it isn’t.<br/>I love grass. <span class="s16">☺</span><br/>
  </p><p class="s13">THE PRESENT CONTINUOUS TENSE FOR ACTIONS IN PROGRESS AND COMPLAINTS</p><p>Is he (it) reading? Yes, he (it) is. / No, he (it) isn’t.<br/><span><IMG width="448" height="323" src="https://app.oxbridge.es/app/movil/FT/Manual S1/Image_310.jpg"/></span><br/>
  </p><p class="s13">THE IMPERATIVE FORMS – AFFIRMATIVE AND NEGATIVE FORMS</p><p class="s30"><u>Students:</u> <span class="s35">you use this structure to </span>give orders <span class="s35">and commands or</span></p><p class="s30">instructions <span class="s35">.</span></p><p class="s15">Form of the imperative</p><p class="s15">Giving Orders:</p><p><span><IMG width="304" height="316" src="https://app.oxbridge.es/app/movil/FT/Manual S1/Image_312.png"/></span><br/>Affirmative form (base form of the verb): Wait!</p><p class="s16">OK, I will wait.</p><p><span><IMG width="433" height="292" src="https://app.oxbridge.es/app/movil/FT/Manual S1/Image_313.png"/></span><br/>Negative short form (Don&#39;t + base form): Don&#39;t wait!</p><p class="s16">OK, I’m leaving.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p class="s13">THE IMPERATIVE FORMS – AFFIRMATIVE AND NEGATIVE FORMS</p><p class="s15">Instructions:</p><p><span><IMG width="386" height="292" src="https://app.oxbridge.es/app/movil/FT/Manual S1/Image_315.png"/></span><br/>Affirmative Instruction: Use a moderate oven and bake for 20 minutes.</p><p class="s16">OK. Thank you for your help</p><p class="s15">Negative Instruction:</p><p><span><IMG width="526" height="243" src="https://app.oxbridge.es/app/movil/FT/Manual S1/Image_316.png"/></span><br/>Don’t touch the cat and feed him at 2 o’clock.</p><p class="s16">Touch me! Touch me!! Pleasseeeee…</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p class="s13">THE IMPERATIVE FORMS – AFFIRMATIVE AND NEGATIVE FORMS</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p class="s13">VERBS EXPRESSING LIKES AND DISLIKES</p><p class="s32">Students: you use this structure to <b>express likes </b>and <b>dislikes </b>(subject + like + verb</p><p class="s32">–ing):</p><p class="s32">There are some verbs in English that express something you LIKE doing and something you DISLIKE doing. It  means that you always like doing it as a HABIT. The most common verbs are:</p><p class="s32">LIKE VERBS:             I love, I like, I enjoy.</p><p class="s32">Eg. I love eating, I like running, I enjoy music.</p><p><span><IMG width="507" height="271" src="https://app.oxbridge.es/app/movil/FT/Manual S1/Image_319.png"/></span></p><p class="s32">Example 1: I like eating meat.</p><p class="s16">Yummy!!! I like eating meat!!!</p><p><span><IMG width="391" height="232" src="https://app.oxbridge.es/app/movil/FT/Manual S1/Image_320.png"/></span></p><p class="s32">Example 2: She/He likes playing football.</p><p class="s16">He likes playing football!!!</p><p><br/><span><IMG width="539" height="317" src="https://app.oxbridge.es/app/movil/FT/Manual S1/Image_322.png"/></span></p><p class="s13">VERBS EXPRESSING LIKES AND DISLIKES</p><p class="s16">Go</p><p class="s16">PP!</p><p class="s32">Example 3: We like talking about politics!!</p><p class="s16">Go</p><p class="s16">CiU!</p><p class="s16">We like talking about politics!!</p><p class="s16">Go</p><p class="s16">PSOE!</p><p class="s32">1.    Expressing dislikes (subject + dislike + verb –ing):</p><p class="s32">DISLIKE VERBS:       I don’t like, Dislike, Hate</p><p class="s32">Eg. I don’t like coming here, I dislike my brother, I hate driving</p><p><span><IMG width="203" height="307" src="https://app.oxbridge.es/app/movil/FT/Manual S1/Image_323.jpg"/></span><br/><span><IMG width="203" height="81" src="https://app.oxbridge.es/app/movil/FT/Manual S1/Image_324.png"/></span></p><p class="s32">Example 1: I dislike eating apples.</p><p class="s16">I dislike eating apples ®</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p class="s13">VERBS EXPRESSING LIKES AND DISLIKES</p><p class="s32">Example 2: She/He dislikes cooking paella.</p><p class="s16">He dislikes cooking paella!</p><p><span><IMG width="572" height="373" src="https://app.oxbridge.es/app/movil/FT/Manual S1/Image_326.png"/></span><br/><span><IMG width="444" height="325" src="https://app.oxbridge.es/app/movil/FT/Manual S1/Image_327.png"/></span></p><p class="s32">Example 3: We dislike getting wet!!!</p><p class="s16">We dislike getting wet!!!</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p class="s13">QUESTIONS AND ANSWERS EXPRESSING LIKES AND DISLIKES</p><p class="s15">Students: <span class="p">Use this structure to </span>ask about likes and dislikes<span class="p">. Also, find the way to quick answer it.</span></p><p>1.  Questions and answers expressing likes with “Do” (Do + subject + like + noun)<br/>Example:      Question: Do you like basketball?<br/><span><IMG width="538" height="235" src="https://app.oxbridge.es/app/movil/FT/Manual S1/Image_329.png"/></span><br/>Answer: Yes, I do/ No, I don’t.</p><p class="s16">Yes, I do!</p><p class="s16">Do you like basketball?</p><p>2.  Questions and answers expressing dislikes with “Do” (Do + subject + dislike + noun)<br/>Example:      Question: Do you dislike the zoo?<br/>Answer: Yes, we do./ No, we don’t.</p><p class="s16">Do you dislike the zoo?</p><p><span><IMG width="130" height="99" src="https://app.oxbridge.es/app/movil/FT/Manual S1/Image_330.png"/></span></p><p class="s16">Yes, we do!!!!</p><p><span><IMG width="401" height="206" src="https://app.oxbridge.es/app/movil/FT/Manual S1/Image_331.png"/></span><br/>3. Questions and answers expressing likes with “What” (What + noun + do + subject + like)<br/>Example:      Question: What food do you like?<br/>
  </p><p class="s13">QUESTIONS AND ANSWERS EXPRESSING LIKES AND DISLIKES</p><p><span><IMG width="468" height="317" src="https://app.oxbridge.es/app/movil/FT/Manual S1/Image_333.png"/></span><br/>Answer: I like Italian food.</p><p class="s16">What food do you like?</p><p class="s16">I like Italian food.</p><p>4.  Questions and answers expressing dislikes with “What” (What + noun + do + subject +dislike)<br/>Example:      Question: What cartoon do you dislike?<br/><span><IMG width="424" height="237" src="https://app.oxbridge.es/app/movil/FT/Manual S1/Image_334.png"/></span><br/><span><IMG width="95" height="94" src="https://app.oxbridge.es/app/movil/FT/Manual S1/Image_335.png"/></span><br/>Answer: I dislike The Simpson’s.</p><p class="s16">What cartoon do you dislike?</p><p class="s16">I dislike The Simpson’s</p><p class="s16">.</p><p>Other verbs that can be used to express likes or dislikes are <b>LOVE </b>(likes) or</p><p class="s15">HATE <span class="p">(dislikes).</span></p><p>&nbsp;</p><p class="s13">ADJECTIVES: FORMS AND POSITIONS</p><p><u><b>Students</b></u>: Here you have a structure that will help you <b>describe people, things and places </b>by learning the forms and position that adjectives take.<br/>Adjectives are important because they are used to give more information on the person, place or thing that you are describing. The most common position of an adjective is before the noun or after the verb. Adjectives don’t change into the plural form even if they go with a plural noun.</p><p class="s15">REMEMBER:</p><p><span><IMG width="106" height="24" src="https://app.oxbridge.es/app/movil/FT/Manual S1/Image_337.png"/></span><br/>1.  Adjectives go before the noun:<br/>a <b>green </b>apple (not: an apple green)<br/><span><IMG width="106" height="24" src="https://app.oxbridge.es/app/movil/FT/Manual S1/Image_338.png"/></span><br/>2.  Adjectives <b>DO NOT </b>change their form for male/female or singular/plural:</p><p class="s15">green <span class="p">apples (not: greens apples)</span></p><p>There are several types of adjectives, here are a few:</p><p class="s15">1. Color<span class="p">: describes the color of something. (Ex: I have a </span>blue <span class="p">jacket.)</span></p><p class="s15">2. Shape<span class="p">: describes the shape of something; its position is before the noun or after the verb to be. (Ex: I have a </span>round <span class="p">ball.)</span></p><p class="s15">3. Age<span class="p">: describes how young or old something / someone is. Its position is normally after the verb ‘to be’. (Ex: It&#39;s my </span>new <span class="p">computer.)</span></p><p class="s15">4. Size<span class="p">: describes the size of someone / something. Its position is before the noun or after the verb ‘to be’ or the noun. (Ex: A </span>small <span class="p">mouse can run fast.)</span></p><p>This is the <b>order of adjectives </b>in a sentence:</p><p class="s15">1. Size</p><p class="s15">2. Age</p><p class="s15">3. Shape</p><p class="s15">4. Color</p><p>For example: It is a small, baby, round, and white seal.<br/><span><IMG width="217" height="163" src="https://app.oxbridge.es/app/movil/FT/Manual S1/Image_339.jpg"/></span><br/>
  </p><p class="s13">ADJECTIVES: FORMS AND POSITIONS</p><p>Here are some more examples of how to use this structure:<br/>1. Using 1 Adjective:<br/>(a) He is an <b>old </b>man. (age)<br/><span><IMG width="291" height="192" src="https://app.oxbridge.es/app/movil/FT/Manual S1/Image_341.jpg"/></span><br/>(b) It is a <b>green </b>apple. (color)<br/><span><IMG width="192" height="189" src="https://app.oxbridge.es/app/movil/FT/Manual S1/Image_342.jpg"/></span><br/>2. Using 2 Adjectives:<br/>(a) She is a <b>short </b>and <b>young </b>girl. (size, age)<br/><span><IMG width="213" height="213" src="https://app.oxbridge.es/app/movil/FT/Manual S1/Image_343.jpg"/></span><br/>
  </p><p class="s13">ADJECTIVES: FORMS AND POSITIONS</p><p>(b) We are <b>thin </b>and <b>pink </b>flamingoes. (size, color)<br/><span><IMG width="255" height="241" src="https://app.oxbridge.es/app/movil/FT/Manual S1/Image_345.gif"/></span><br/>3. Using 3 Adjectives:<br/><span><IMG width="188" height="231" src="https://app.oxbridge.es/app/movil/FT/Manual S1/Image_346.jpg"/></span><br/>(a) He is a <b>short, oval </b>and <b>orang</b>e cat. (size, shape, color)<br/>(b) We are <b>tall, young </b>and <b>thin </b>models. (size, age, shape)<br/><span><IMG width="148" height="223" src="https://app.oxbridge.es/app/movil/FT/Manual S1/Image_347.jpg"/></span><br/>
  </p><p class="s13">ADJECTIVES: FORMS AND POSITIONS</p><p>4. Using 4 adjective<br/>color)<br/>(a) He is a <b>tall, young, muscular </b>and <b>white </b>man. (size, age, shape,<br/><span><IMG width="191" height="323" src="https://app.oxbridge.es/app/movil/FT/Manual S1/Image_349.jpg"/></span><br/>(b) They are tall, middle aged, round and white golfers. (size, age, shape, color)<br/><span><IMG width="351" height="279" src="https://app.oxbridge.es/app/movil/FT/Manual S1/Image_350.jpg"/></span><br/>
  </p><p class="s13">EXPRESSING TIME: ASKING AND SAYING TIME. 24 HOUR CLOCK. PARTS OF THE DAY</p><p class="s15">Students: <span class="p">It is very important to know this structure because you will know how to</span></p><p class="s15">express time <span class="p">and </span>parts of the day<span class="p">.</span></p><p>To ask for the time, we use: <b>WHAT TIME IS IT?</b><br/>In English we use ´<b>PAST </b>´ to express when the time is after the hour until half past, or 30 minutes past the hour.<br/>For example: It is 7:15 PM (a quarter <b>past </b>seven) It is 7:30 PM (half <b>past </b>seven)<br/>We use ´<b>TO</b>´ to express the time before the hour from 31 minutes until the full hour.<br/>For example: It is 7:45 PM (a quarter <b>to </b>eight) It is 7: 55PM (five <b>to </b>eight)<br/>In English we use ‘<b>O’CLOCK</b>” only at the full hour. For example: It is 7:00PM (seven <b>o’clock</b>)<br/>It is 6:00PM (six <b>o’clock</b>)<br/>In English we can say the numbers in groups of two. For example: It is 7:21PM (seven twenty-one)<br/>It is 7:34 PM (seven thirty-four)<br/>When we want to talk/refer to the different times of the day we often use<b>: ‘in the morning’, ‘in the afternoon’ and ‘in the evening’.</b><br/>Warning!!! in English we don’t use ‘at night’. Please be aware that these references for the time of the day are not necessary to use; they are optional when someone asks you the time of when you ask the time.<br/>More ways of asking about the time:</p><p class="s15">-What time is it?</p><p>-What’s the time?<br/>-Have you got the time?<br/>-What time do you have?<br/>Now, here you have some English phrases on how to tell time:<br/>-If someone asks you the time, you can say &quot;The time is...(eight o’clock)&quot; or, more common, &quot;It’s…(half past 3).&quot;.<br/>
  </p><p class="s13">EXPRESSING TIME: ASKING AND SAYING TIME. 24 HOUR CLOCK. PARTS OF THE DAY</p><p class="s15">Here is an example of a dialogue:</p><p>Person 1: “What’s the time, please?”<br/>Person 2: “It’s seven o’clock (7:00AM) (in the morning)”<br/>This structure is very easy, but here are some more examples with dialogue included:<br/>(a)  - What’s the time, please?<br/>- It’s 3:10 (three past eight) (in the afternoon)<br/><span><IMG width="316" height="281" src="https://app.oxbridge.es/app/movil/FT/Manual S1/Image_353.png"/></span><br/>- Thank you.</p><p class="s16">Ok. Lets go for a drink ☺</p><p>(b) - Excuse me, have you got the time?<br/>- Yes. It’s 8:52AM (eight to nine) (in the morning).<br/><span><IMG width="338" height="271" src="https://app.oxbridge.es/app/movil/FT/Manual S1/Image_354.png"/></span><br/>- Thank you.</p><p class="s16">Great! So we need to eat breakfast!</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p class="s13">EXPRESSING TIME: ASKING AND SAYING TIME. 24 HOUR CLOCK. PARTS OF THE DAY</p><p>(c) - Pardon, what time do you have?<br/>- It’s 9:00 PM (nine o’clock).<br/><span><IMG width="352" height="275" src="https://app.oxbridge.es/app/movil/FT/Manual S1/Image_356.png"/></span><br/>- OK. Thank you.</p><p class="s16">We need</p><p class="s16">to go now!</p><p>(d)  - What’ the time, please?<br/>- It’s 10:19PM (ten nineteen)<br/><span><IMG width="310" height="257" src="https://app.oxbridge.es/app/movil/FT/Manual S1/Image_357.png"/></span><br/>- Thanks.</p><p class="s16">I am going to sleep, then.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p class="s13">EXPRESSING TIME: “WHEN / WHAT TIME…?”</p><p>Students: You’ll learn how to <b>ask and answer questions about the TIME</b>. Normally, we ask these questions when we want to know <b>when and what</b></p><p class="s15">time we do a ROUTINE.</p><p class="s15">What time do you …? – At …</p><p class="s15">When …? – In + <span class="p">months</span>, On <span class="p">+ days, </span>At <span class="p">+ hours</span></p><p>For example:<br/>- If you ask “what time…?” the answer should usually be an exact time.<br/>- If you ask “when…?” you can answer with an indefinite time: in the morning, on weekends, during the holidays, etc.<br/>Here you have some examples of the above information: What time do you take shower? At 8 o’clock.<br/>What time does your boss go home? At 7:35 PM What time do they go shopping? At 5:30 PM<br/>When do you go to the beach? I go on the weekends. When does your father visit you? During the holidays. When do you rest? In the afternoon.<br/>If you need some more revision on this structure please use the example below to help you understand the concept. Here are the examples:<br/>1.  ‘WHAT TIME…?’ examples:<br/>(a) What time does he have lunch?<br/><span><IMG width="210" height="157" src="https://app.oxbridge.es/app/movil/FT/Manual S1/Image_359.jpg"/></span><br/>-At 2 o’clock.<br/>Yummy!<br/>
  </p><p class="s13">EXPRESSING TIME: “WHEN / WHAT TIME…?”</p><p>(b) What time do they finish class?<br/>-At 2:35 PM.<br/><span><IMG width="427" height="286" src="https://app.oxbridge.es/app/movil/FT/Manual S1/Image_361.gif"/></span><br/>One more hour and we’re done <span class="s16">☺</span><br/>(c) What time do we go to Caprabo?<br/><span><IMG width="248" height="356" src="https://app.oxbridge.es/app/movil/FT/Manual S1/Image_362.jpg"/></span><br/>-At 4:45 PM.<br/>I’m finally finished!<br/>
  </p><p class="s13">EXPRESSING TIME: “WHEN / WHAT TIME…?”</p><p>2.  ‘WHEN…?’ examples:<br/>(a) When does she go to the gym?<br/><span><IMG width="436" height="289" src="https://app.oxbridge.es/app/movil/FT/Manual S1/Image_364.jpg"/></span><br/>-In the evening.<br/>I am always at the gym <span class="s16">☺</span><br/>(b) When do you go sleep?<br/><span><IMG width="379" height="291" src="https://app.oxbridge.es/app/movil/FT/Manual S1/Image_365.jpg"/></span><br/>-During the night.<br/>I’m so sleepy!!!<br/>
  </p><p class="s13">EXPRESSING TIME: “WHEN / WHAT TIME…?”</p><p>(c) When do they gossip?<br/><span><IMG width="339" height="233" src="https://app.oxbridge.es/app/movil/FT/Manual S1/Image_367.jpg"/></span><br/>-In the afternoon.</p><p class="s16">Ana Obregon is pregnant!</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p class="s13">PREPOSITIONS OF TIME: IN, ON, AT, AFTER, BEFORE</p><p class="s15">Students: <span class="p">Here you have yet another structure that will help you </span>express time<span class="p">. Here is how we use them in English:</span></p><p class="s15">AT <span class="p">for HOURS and PRECISE TIME</span></p><p class="s15">IN <span class="p">for MONTHS, YEARS, CENTURIES and LONG PERIODS</span></p><p class="s15">ON <span class="p">for DAYS and DATES</span></p><p>Here is a chart with some brief example of the above prepositions:</p><table border="1" cellspacing="0" style="border-collapse:collapse"><tr><td><p class="s27">At</p></td><td><p class="s27">In</p></td><td><p class="s27">on</p></td></tr><tr><td><p class="s27">PRECISE TIME</p></td><td><p class="s27">MONTHS, YEARS, CENTURIES and</p><p class="s27">LONG PERIODS</p></td><td><p class="s27">DAYS and DATES</p></td></tr><tr><td><p class="s19">at 3 o&#39;clock</p></td><td><p class="s19">in May</p></td><td><p class="s19">on Sunday</p></td></tr><tr><td><p class="s19">at 10.30am</p></td><td><p class="s19">in summer</p></td><td><p class="s19">on Tuesdays</p></td></tr><tr><td><p class="s19">at noon</p></td><td><p class="s19">in the summer</p></td><td><p class="s19">on 6 March</p></td></tr><tr><td><p class="s19">at dinnertime</p></td><td><p class="s19">in 1990</p></td><td><p class="s19">on 25 Dec. 2010</p></td></tr><tr><td><p class="s19">at bedtime</p></td><td><p class="s19">in the 1990s</p></td><td><p class="s19">on Christmas Day</p></td></tr><tr><td><p class="s19">at sunrise</p></td><td><p class="s19">in the next century</p></td><td><p class="s19">on Independence</p><p class="s19">Day</p></td></tr><tr><td><p class="s19">at sunset</p></td><td><p class="s19">in the Ice Age</p></td><td><p class="s19">on my birthday</p></td></tr><tr><td><p class="s19">at the moment</p></td><td><p class="s19">in the past/future</p></td><td><p class="s19">on New Year&#39;s Eve</p></td></tr></table><p>We use <b>AFTER </b>and <b>BEFORE </b>to indicate actions occurring at different times.</p><p class="s15">BEFORE <span class="p">is to indicate something that happened before another time or event (past event) and something that happened earlier in a series.</span></p><p class="s36"><span class="p">For example: </span>I wash my face <b>before </b>I go to sleep.</p><p class="s15">AFTER <span class="p">is used to indicate something that happened later in time, later in a series, and to be in pursuit of something.</span></p><p>For example: I go to sleep <b>after </b>dinner.<br/>
  </p><p class="s13">PREPOSITIONS OF TIME: IN, ON, AT, AFTER, BEFORE</p><p>Here you have some examples of the prepositions of time (at, in, on, before, after):<br/>1.  AT:<br/>I have a meeting <b>at </b>9am.<br/><span><IMG width="176" height="165" src="https://app.oxbridge.es/app/movil/FT/Manual S1/Image_370.jpg"/></span><br/>The shop closes <b>at </b>midnight.<br/><span><IMG width="239" height="180" src="https://app.oxbridge.es/app/movil/FT/Manual S1/Image_371.jpg"/></span><br/>2.  IN:<br/>In England, it often snows <b>in </b>December.<br/><span><IMG width="250" height="189" src="https://app.oxbridge.es/app/movil/FT/Manual S1/Image_372.gif"/></span><br/>
  </p><p class="s13">PREPOSITIONS OF TIME: IN, ON, AT, AFTER, BEFORE</p><p class="s15">In <span class="p">the future we want to go to Jupiter?</span></p><p><span><IMG width="260" height="203" src="https://app.oxbridge.es/app/movil/FT/Manual S1/Image_374.jpg"/></span><br/>3.  ON:<br/>Do you work <b>on </b>Mondays?<br/><span><IMG width="270" height="194" src="https://app.oxbridge.es/app/movil/FT/Manual S1/Image_375.jpg"/></span><br/><span><IMG width="172" height="224" src="https://app.oxbridge.es/app/movil/FT/Manual S1/Image_376.jpg"/></span><br/>Her birthday is <b>on </b>11 October.<br/>(1 year old Adri <span class="s16">☺</span>)<br/>
  </p><p class="s13">PREPOSITIONS OF TIME: IN, ON, AT, AFTER, BEFORE</p><p>4.  BEFORE:<br/>I go shopping before Christmas.<br/><span><IMG width="174" height="240" src="https://app.oxbridge.es/app/movil/FT/Manual S1/Image_378.jpg"/></span><br/>We have lunch before we go to the gym.<br/><span><IMG width="335" height="218" src="https://app.oxbridge.es/app/movil/FT/Manual S1/Image_379.jpg"/></span><br/>5.  AFTER:<br/>The dog runs after the cat.<br/><span><IMG width="339" height="202" src="https://app.oxbridge.es/app/movil/FT/Manual S1/Image_380.jpg"/></span><br/>
  </p><p class="s13">PREPOSITIONS OF TIME: IN, ON, AT, AFTER, BEFORE</p><p>I study after classes.<br/><span><IMG width="207" height="276" src="https://app.oxbridge.es/app/movil/FT/Manual S1/Image_382.jpg"/></span><br/>
  </p><p class="s13">BASIC WH- QUESTIONS</p><p class="s15">Students: <span class="p">With this structure you learn how to </span>ask questions <span class="p">in English. Please be aware that there are different types of questions that help you ask and know different things.</span></p><p>Here you have the structure when you want to make a question:</p><p class="s15">Wh- question + Auxiliary (do/does) + Subject + Complement</p><p class="s15">Wh- question + TO BE + Subject + Complement</p><p>Usage of question words in English:</p><p class="s15">• Who?</p><p>We use this type of question to <b>ask about people</b>. Ex. Who is she? She’s my sister.</p><p class="s15">• What?</p><p>We use this type of question to <b>ask about things</b>. Ex. What is this? This is a pencil.</p><p class="s15">• Where?</p><p>We use this type of question to <b>ask about a place</b>/location. Ex. Where do you live? I live in Barcelona.</p><p class="s15">• When?</p><p>We use this type of question to <b>ask about an indefinite time</b>. Ex. When do you finish? I finish at 7 o’clock.</p><p class="s15">• What time?</p><p>We use this type of question to <b>ask about specific time.</b><br/>Ex. What time do you wake up? I wake up at 8:00 AM.</p><p class="s15">• Why?</p><p>We use this type of question to <b>ask about reason</b>. Ex. Why do you eat? Because I’ hungry.</p><p class="s15">• How?</p><p>We use this type of question to <b>ask about </b>manner or <b>way of doing something</b>.<br/>Ex. How do you get to work? I get to work by Metro.</p><p class="s15">• How much?</p><p>We use this type of question to <b>ask about uncountable quantities</b>. Ex. How much does it cost? It costs 5 euros.</p><p class="s15">• How many?</p><p>We use this type of question to <b>ask about countable quantities</b>.<br/>
  </p><p class="s13">BASIC WH- QUESTIONS</p><p>Ex. How many sisters do you have? I have one sister.</p><p class="s15">• How old?</p><p>We use this type of question to <b>ask about age</b>. Ex. How old is your grandpa? He is 82.<br/>**If you need to make a question and you need to use a preposition, it MUST go at the end of the sentence:<br/>Ex.     What is this paper <b>for</b>?<br/>Who do you go <b>with</b>?</p><p class="s38">**Here are some examples of wh- questions with pictures:</p><p>• Who?<br/>Who is your favorite actor?<br/>My favorite actor is Gael Garcia Bernal.<br/><span><IMG width="166" height="203" src="https://app.oxbridge.es/app/movil/FT/Manual S1/Image_385.jpg"/></span><br/>• What?<br/>What do you like eating? I like eating spaghetti.<br/><span><IMG width="128" height="150" src="https://app.oxbridge.es/app/movil/FT/Manual S1/Image_386.jpg"/></span><br/>
  </p><p class="s13">BASIC WH- QUESTIONS</p><p>• Where?<br/>Where do you live? We live in Mallorca.<br/><span><IMG width="380" height="311" src="https://app.oxbridge.es/app/movil/FT/Manual S1/Image_388.jpg"/></span><br/>• When?<br/>When does she go to the cinema? She goes on Saturday.<br/><span><IMG width="464" height="293" src="https://app.oxbridge.es/app/movil/FT/Manual S1/Image_389.png"/></span><br/>
  </p><p class="s13">BASIC WH- QUESTIONS</p><p>• Why?<br/>Why does she smoke? Because she likes it. (present)<br/><span><IMG width="311" height="225" src="https://app.oxbridge.es/app/movil/FT/Manual S1/Image_391.jpg"/></span><br/>• What time?<br/>What time is it now? It’s 10:13 PM.<br/><span><IMG width="194" height="194" src="https://app.oxbridge.es/app/movil/FT/Manual S1/Image_392.jpg"/></span><br/>• How?<br/>How do they make a cake?<br/>They make it with eggs and sugar.<br/><span><IMG width="328" height="135" src="https://app.oxbridge.es/app/movil/FT/Manual S1/Image_393.png"/></span><br/>
  </p><p class="s13">BASIC WH- QUESTIONS</p><p>• How much?<br/>How much does it cost? It costs 1.000 euros.<br/><span><IMG width="224" height="154" src="https://app.oxbridge.es/app/movil/FT/Manual S1/Image_395.jpg"/></span><br/>• How many?<br/>How many cats are there? There are 2 cats.<br/><span><IMG width="280" height="210" src="https://app.oxbridge.es/app/movil/FT/Manual S1/Image_396.jpg"/></span><br/>• How old?<br/>How old is she? She is 1.<br/><span><IMG width="142" height="205" src="https://app.oxbridge.es/app/movil/FT/Manual S1/Image_397.jpg"/></span><br/>
  </p><p class="s13">EXPRESSING ABILITIES: “CAN / CAN’T”</p><p class="s14">Students<span class="p">: Here you have yet another useful structure. With this structure you can talk about things you can and can’t do, also, ask questions with “can”.</span></p><p>Formula:</p><p class="s16">-    <span class="s15">Can you …?</span></p><p class="s16">-    <span class="s15">Yes, I can. / No, I can’t.</span></p><p>*** <b>Can </b>is the same for all subjects: I, you, she, he, it, we, they.<br/>*** We don’t add “–s” for he, she, it: <b>She can </b>swim. (She cans swim <span class="s16">-7 </span>wrong!!)<br/>Please make sure you know that ‘CAN’ expresses mainly <b>ability</b>. Here are some usages:</p><p class="s15">1) ‘Can’ as a general ability. This means to be able to do something.</p><p>Examples:<br/>a) I <b>can </b>swim fast.<br/><span><IMG width="271" height="179" src="https://app.oxbridge.es/app/movil/FT/Manual S1/Image_399.jpg"/></span></p><p class="s13">(I am fast)</p><p><span><IMG width="229" height="196" src="https://app.oxbridge.es/app/movil/FT/Manual S1/Image_400.jpg"/></span><br/>b) I <b>can&#39;t </b>swim fast.</p><p class="s16">(<span class="s39">I am slow)</span></p><p>&nbsp;</p><p class="s13">EXPRESSING ABILITIES: “CAN / CAN’T”</p><p class="s15">2) ‘Can’ as opportunity or to have the opportunity to do something.</p><p>Examples:<br/>a) We can go to Italy.<br/><span><IMG width="184" height="277" src="https://app.oxbridge.es/app/movil/FT/Manual S1/Image_402.jpg"/></span></p><p class="s13">(we love Italy!)</p><p>b) I can’t go to England.<br/><span><IMG width="240" height="328" src="https://app.oxbridge.es/app/movil/FT/Manual S1/Image_403.jpg"/></span></p><p class="s13">(I must go to California)</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p class="s13">EXPRESSING ABILITIES: “CAN / CAN’T”</p><p class="s15">3) ‘Can’ as permission or request.</p><p>Examples:<br/>a)  My brother can’t go to the park because he is punished.<br/><span><IMG width="320" height="320" src="https://app.oxbridge.es/app/movil/FT/Manual S1/Image_405.jpg"/></span><br/>b)  We can go to the zoo because we are good girls.<br/><span><IMG width="450" height="315" src="https://app.oxbridge.es/app/movil/FT/Manual S1/Image_406.jpg"/></span><br/>
  </p><p class="s13">EXPRESSING ABILITIES: “CAN / CAN’T”</p><p class="s13">(We love the zoo!)</p><p class="s15">4) ‘Can’ as possibility or impossibility.</p><p>Examples:<br/>a)  Anyone can work.<br/><span><IMG width="452" height="320" src="https://app.oxbridge.es/app/movil/FT/Manual S1/Image_408.jpg"/></span></p><p class="s13">(Lets go to work!)</p><p>b)  We can’t finish.<br/><span><IMG width="354" height="248" src="https://app.oxbridge.es/app/movil/FT/Manual S1/Image_409.jpg"/></span></p><p class="s13">(I’m so tired!!! <span class="s39">☺</span>)</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p class="s13">EXPRESSING ABILITIES: “CAN / CAN’T”</p><p class="s15">5) ‘Can’ in question format.</p><p>a)  Can she cook? (ability) (Yes, she can. / No, she can’t.)<br/><span><IMG width="138" height="182" src="https://app.oxbridge.es/app/movil/FT/Manual S1/Image_411.gif"/></span></p><p class="s13">(yummy!)</p><p><span><IMG width="300" height="202" src="https://app.oxbridge.es/app/movil/FT/Manual S1/Image_412.jpg"/></span><br/>b)  Can you go to the university? (opportunity / possibility) (Yes, I can. No, I can’t.)<br/><span><IMG width="161" height="160" src="https://app.oxbridge.es/app/movil/FT/Manual S1/Image_413.png"/></span></p><p class="s13">(Middlebury is fantastic university.)</p><p><span><IMG width="157" height="175" src="https://app.oxbridge.es/app/movil/FT/Manual S1/Image_414.gif"/></span><br/>c)  Can your father eat junk food? (permission) (Yes, he can. / No, he can’t.)</p><p class="s39">(I love McDonald’s.)</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p class="s13">EMAIL WRITING</p><h3>Writing E-mails (formal and informal)</h3><p>STUDENTS: The basics of good email or letter writing are easy to learn. The following guide provides the phrases that are usually found in any standard email or letter. At<br/><span><IMG width="314" height="338" src="https://app.oxbridge.es/app/movil/FT/Manual S1/Image_416.png"/></span><br/>the end of this guide, you will find links to sites that give tips on the difficult part of writing successful emails or letters. By using these standard phrases, you can give a professional tone to your English emails or letters.</p><p class="s16">ADDRESS</p><p class="s16">BODY</p><p class="s16">SIGNATURE</p><p><span><IMG width="7" height="3" src="https://app.oxbridge.es/app/movil/FT/Manual S1/Image_417.png"/></span></p><p class="s40">ADRESSES<span class="s41">:</span></p><p class="s33">- FORMAL:</p><p class="s32">1. Dear Personnel Director,</p><p class="s32">2. Dear Sir or Madam: (use if you don&#39;t know who you are writing to)</p><p class="s32">3. Dear Dr., Mr., Mrs., Miss or Ms. Smith: (use if you know who you are writing to, and have a formal relationship with - <b>VERY IMPORTANT </b>use Ms.</p><p class="s32">for                                     women unless asked to use Mrs. or Miss)</p><p class="s33">- INFORMAL:</p><p class="s32">1. Dear Frank: (use if the person is a close business contact or friend)</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p class="s13">EMAIL WRITING</p><p class="s32">2. Hello/hi Frank!</p><p class="s42">BODY STRUCTURE (FORMAL AND INFORMAL) :</p><p class="s33">-The Reason for Writing</p><p class="s32">I am writing to inquire about apologize for confirm</p><p class="s33">-Requesting</p><p class="s32">Could you possibly?</p><p class="s32">I would be grateful if you could</p><p class="s33">-Agreeing to Requests</p><p class="s32">I would be delighted to</p><p class="s33">-Giving Bad News</p><p class="s32">Unfortunately</p><p class="s32">I am afraid that</p><p class="s33">-Enclosing Documents</p><p class="s32">I am enclosing Please find enclosed Enclosed you will find</p><p class="s33">-Closing Remarks</p><p class="s32">Thank you</p><p class="s32">Hope to hear from you soon</p><p class="s32">Keep in touch</p><p class="s33">-The Finish</p><p class="s32">Yours faithfully, (If you don&#39;t know the name of the person you&#39;re writing to) Yours sincerely, (If you know the name of the person you&#39;re writing to)</p><p class="s32">Best wishes,</p><p class="s32">Best regards, (If the person is a close business contact or friend)</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p class="s13">EMAIL WRITING</p><p class="s43">SIGNATURE:</p><p class="s33">- FORMAL:</p><p class="s32">-Use your full name, add your profession or who/what you represent, and your contact information.</p><p class="s32">For example:  Jennifer Brown</p><p class="s32">Senior Vice-President of TV-3</p><p class="s32">Email: <a href="mailto:janebrown@tv3.com" class="s44"> </a><a href="mailto:janebrown@tv3.com" class="s45">janebrown@tv3.com</a></p><p class="s32">Mobile #: 675.111.000</p><p class="s32">Fax: 93.567.9887</p><p class="s33">- INFORMAL:</p><p class="s32">-If you are sending an email to a friend you only need to add your first name or your nickname and nothing because you are contacting them for</p><p class="s32">personal                                    reasons, not professional reasons.</p><p class="s32">For example:  Jenny</p><p class="s46">SAMPLE LETTER:</p><p class="s32">Dear Mr. Flintstone:</p><p class="s32">With reference to our telephone conversation today, I am writing to confirm your order for: 120 x Cheddar Deluxe Ref. No. 856.</p><p class="s32">The order will be shipped within three days via UPS and should arrive at your store in about</p><p class="s32">10 days.</p><p class="s32">Please contact us again if we can help in any way. Yours sincerely,</p><p class="s32">Kenneth W. Berry</p><p class="s32">Director of Ken&#39;s Cheese House</p><p class="s32">Email: <a href="mailto:kenny@cheese.com" class="s45">kenny@cheese.com</a></p><p class="s32">Mobile #: 675.111.000</p><p class="s32">Fax: 93.567.9887</p><p>&nbsp;</p>
